<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday, Feb. 6, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Jet Lands After Problem
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- An Alaska Airlines MD-80 jet returned to Reno's airport
shortly after takeoff on Saturday night after its pilot reported problems
similar to those under investigation in Monday's crash off the California coast,
officials said. The Seattle-bound flight left Reno/Tahoe International Airport
at about 7 p.m. and returned after about eight minutes later after the pilot
reported motors controlling the plane's horizontal stabilizer were operating
improperly, said Jack Evans, an Alaska Airlines spokesman. Investigators are
looking into possible problems with the stabilizer on Alaska Flight 261, an
MD-83 which crashed on Monday in the Pacific Ocean north of Los Angeles, killing
88 people.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Crash Victim's Ring Given to Family
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   POULSBO, Wash. (AP) -- A California fisherman who recovered a Masonic ring
belonging to a victim of last week's Alaska Airlines crash presented it to the
man's children Saturday. The ring's owner, Bob Williams, and his wife, Patty,
died along with 86 others aboard Flight 261 from Puerto Vallarta when the plane
went down Monday off the coast of southern California. The ring has become a
meaningful symbol for the remaining family members, said Williams' daughter,
Tracy Knizek.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Seven Die in German Train Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BRUEHL, Germany (AP) -- An overnight express train derailed early Sunday
near Cologne, killing at least seven passengers and injuring more than 100,
authorities said. The sleeper train, headed from Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to
Basel, Switzerland with about 300 passengers, went off the tracks shortly after
midnight at a switch in the small town of Bruehl, south of Cologne, German
railways spokesman Manfred Ziegerath said. The engine tumbled down an embankment
and crashed through the garage of a house, but the people inside were unscathed,
police said. Most of those killed had been either in a car that fell down the
embankment or another that hit a steel post, officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Woman Found Dead at Columbia U.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A university student was found dead in her dorm room on
Saturday, and her boyfriend, considered a suspect in her death, died hours later
after throwing himself in front of a subway train, police said. Kathleen Roskot,
19, a Columbia University student from Long Island, was found dead in her
bedroom with a stab wound to the neck, police said. She was discovered by a
resident assistant after she failed to show up for lacrosse practice, Columbia
spokeswoman Suzanne Trimel said. Authorities said a kitchen knife believed to be
the weapon had been left in a bathroom.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IRA's Disarmament in Doubt
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Irish Republican Army commanders said
Saturday that British and Protestant demands will not influence whether or not
they disarm, leaving the centerpiece of Northern Ireland's peace accord, the
Protestant-Catholic government, in continued peril. The British government says
it intends to strip the 9-week-old coalition Cabinet of its powers on Friday if
the IRA doesn't promise to disarm. The province's Cabinet was formed two months
ago following a Sinn Fein-Ulster Unionist deal brokered by American mediator
George Mitchell.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: McCain Catches Bush in S.C.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Time/CNN poll released Saturday says John McCain has
rallied from a 20-percent point deficit against George W. Bush in South Carolina
and is now in a statistical draw. The latest poll found McCain the choice of 44
percent of likely Republican voters in the Feb. 19 primary, compared with Bush's
40 percent. Nationally, a Newsweek poll showed a major surge by McCain after a
resounding victory in New Hampshire, but found he still was far behind the Texas
governor.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Magic Defeat the Pacers 107-102
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Reserve Chucky Atkins scored 15 of his 17 points in
the fourth quarter as the Orlando Magic snapped Indiana's four-game winning
streak with a 107-102 victory Saturday night. John Amaechi had 19 points and Pat
Garrity added 18 for the Magic, but it was Atkins who came through down the
stretch. The backup point guard scored seven of Orlando's last nine points,
including a driving one-hand runner that put his team up 103-97 with 49 seconds
to go. Jalen Rose led Indiana with 25 points, however the Pacers only got 13
from Reggie Miller on 3-for-8 shooting to lose for the fifth straight time on
the road.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Knocked Out of America's Cup
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Prada skipper Francesco de Angelis sailed
brilliantly Sunday, beating AmericaOne by 49 seconds in the deciding race of the
America's Cup challenger finals. So for the first time in the Cup's 150-year
history, no U.S. boat will compete in the finals. Prada capped its comeback from
a 4-3 deficit and advanced to face defending champion New Zealand in the
best-of-9 Cup finals starting Feb. 19 for the shiny silver pitcher that is
sailing's top prize.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
