<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Die in German Train Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By JOACHIM SONDERMANN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRUEHL, Germany (AP) -- A European night train hurtled off the tracks early
Sunday in a southern suburb of Cologne, killing at least seven passengers and
injuring more than 100, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
	   One car toppled down an embankment and another was crushed against a steel
post when the sleeper train derailed shortly after midnight at a switch in the
small town of Bruehl, German railways spokesman Manfred Ziegerath said.
</P>
<P>
	   The train was heading from Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to Basel, Switzerland
with about 300 passengers.
</P>
<P>
	   Scores of rescue workers using heavy equipment and dogs broke open the
mangled blue coaches and combed the debris throughout the night. As day broke
over the floodlit scene, rescue crews prepared to lift wrecked coaches, under
which police said more dead might be found.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said the train's engine had fallen down the embankment, smashed
through the garage of a house but stopped just before the house wall. The people
inside were unscathed.
</P>
<P>
	   Damage was the worst in the second coach, which was pulled with the engine
over the embankment, and in another car that had slammed into a support pole
under the Bruehl station roof.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I was already sleeping, and then a big crash woke me up,'' said a woman
living about 300 feet from the crash site who declined to give her name. ``I've
never heard so many sirens.''
</P>
<P>
	   Seven people were killed and 105 were taken to hospitals, including about 20
with serious injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Witnesses said many young people had been on the train. The train driver was
not injured, but was in shock, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   The nine-car train had just left Cologne main station on one of Germany's
main international routes when it derailed at 12:13 a.m. after crossing a series
of switches to avoid track work, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ziegerath said the train left the tracks at a switch when it returned to the
main line.
</P>
<P>
	   Railway authorities and prosecutors were investigating the cause of the
accident, Germany's deadliest since the June 1998 crash of a high-speed
IntercityExpress that killed 101 people at Eschede. The cause of that crash was
found to be a broken wheel.
</P>
<P>
	   Sunday's crash seemed certain to revive questions about German rail safety
lingering since the Eschede disaster. The railways set up a telephone hotline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 0316 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
