<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinking demonstrates how immersion suits save lives  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PORTLAND, Maine (AP) - As his trawler filled with seawater and heaved
back and forth in vicious waves, Shawn Rich scrambled to climb into his
immersion suit.
<P>
	   The bulky suit proved to be a lifesaver, keeping the fisherman from freezing
to death as he was tossed about on the rough seas for three hours, awaiting
rescue.
</P>
<P>
	   The Coast Guard credits immersion suits as one of the key factors behind a
dramatic drop in deaths in the fishing fleet.
</P>
<P>
	   The suits are critically important when vessels go down swiftly. Rich
testified last week at a formal inquiry into the sinking of his trawler, Two
Friends, that he didn't even have time to get the life raft into the water
before his 63-foot vessel flooded and capsized.
</P>
<P>
	   "People think a boat sinking takes a lot of time but it doesn't. It can
happen in less than a minute," said Leni Gronros, president of Rockland Boat,
the only place in Maine licensed to repair immersion suits.
</P>
<P>
	   The Coast Guard has required vessels in cold waters to be equipped with
immersion suits since the early 1990s, the same time requirements for emergency
locator devices and life rafts went into effect.
</P>
<P>
	   Together, those three safety items are credited with saving more than 200
lives since 1993 from Maine to northern New Jersey, said Bob Higgins, a Coast
Guard regional fishing vessel safety coordinator in Boston.
</P>
<P>
	   The number of deaths in the fishing industry in the region was cut in half
in the same period, Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Alaskan commercial fishery also has seen a big drop in the number of
deaths because of the safety measures.
</P>
<P>
	   The death rate associated with vessel losses in Alaska dropped from 27
percent to 7 percent between 1991 and 1998 even though the number of sinkings
remained about the same, said Jennifer Lincoln of the National Institute for
Occupational Safety and Health.
</P>
<P>
	   The bulky suits, which sell for $250 to $350, are made for a fishermen to
step into while wearing boots and clothes.
</P>
<P>
	   The fisherman gets into the one-size-fits-all suit like overalls, puts his
arms through the sleeves, pulls up the entry zipper, and then positions a hood
and mittens. Air bladders make the suits buoyant, and fishermen are advised to
simply float on their backs until help arrives.
</P>
<P>
	   Unfortunately, many fishermen have complied with the Coast Guard requirement
by tossing the suits aboard a vessel and never thinking about them again,
Gronros said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's viewed as a nuisance to a lot of people and that's too bad," Gronros
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Getting into an immersion suit requires practice and suits that are not
maintained may suffer from dry rot, leaky seams and zippers that do not work,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
	   Rich, the only survivor of the three-member crew, testified at the inquiry
that the Two Friends began taking on water off Cape Neddick on Jan. 25 and
shifted suddenly. Within minutes, it capsized.
</P>
<P>
	   Rich managed to climb into his suit but did not get his head covered because
his sweatshirt interfered.
</P>
<P>
	   The skipper, who died as Rich tried to keep his head afloat, was not able to
get one of his arms into his suit. When the body was recovered, one of his arms
was in a position as if he had been tugging at the zipper, according to a
statement by a Coast Guard swimmer.
</P>
<P>
	   The other victim, Rich's father, got into the suit but was caught under the
vessel when it capsized, Rich testified.
</P>
<P>
	   Stewart Tweed, who works for Rutgers Cooperative Extension, which promotes a
safety program in New Jersey, said it's important for fishermen to conduct
monthly safety drills.
</P>
<P>
	   The two-day course sponsored by Rutgers required fishermen to practice
putting on their immersion suits and to get into a pool wearing the cumbersome
suits, Tweed said.
</P>
<P>
	   "You can have all of the gear in the world, but if you don't know how to use
it, it's not useful," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Coast Guard said the inquiry into the Two Friends highlighted some
potential problems with immersion suits and there may be lessons to be learned
in preparedness, said James Shelton, a Coast Guard spokesman who attended an
official inquiry into the sinking.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's one of the things that may come out of this, a stepped-up approach
in terms of training," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1236 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> It's pork to McCain but gold to others in Congress  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - The John McCain road show stops briefly in New Jersey
this week, energized by a huge primary victory in New Hampshire built upon the
candidate's "straight talk" criticism of money in politics and pork-barrel
government spending.
<P>
	   "My gosh, after Tuesday's results (in New Hampshire) that thing is going
bananas," said state Sen. William Schluter, a McCain supporter, describing
ticket sales for this Friday's $500-a-person fundraiser at Fiddler's Elbow
Country Club in Somerset County.
</P>
<P>
	   If the Republican senator from Arizona delivers his standard stump speech,
his New Jersey supporters will hear this from McCain:
</P>
<P>
	   "I will refuse to sign any pork barrel bill that crosses my desk. And if
Congress tries to make me waste your money, I will make sure you know who they
are - every single one of them."
</P>
<P>
	   One lawmaker's pork is another's gold, however.
</P>
<P>
	   The pork that McCain rails against includes funding for some activities
cherished by New Jersey and zealously guarded by its lawmakers in both parties:
cancer research in Toms River, beach replenishment up and down the coast,
military construction projects at Fort Dix and Naval Weapons Station Earle.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's commitment to pork-busting is evident on his official Senate site
on the World Wide Web. A pig rolls a barrel of dollars across the site to
illustrate the senator's devotion to cutting pork-barrel spending.
</P>
<P>
	   Click on the pig and you find long lists of pork projects that McCain railed
against last year. Taken from appropriations bills approved by Congress, the
lists include dozens of earmarked funds for the Garden State.
</P>
<P>
	   They include $500,000 to the State Police for a truck safety initiative,
$400,000 to Monmouth University for a teacher skill project and $2.5 million for
a computer network at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, $1.5 million to research cancer cases in Toms River and $500,000 for
downtown revitalization in Gloucester County.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, $1.25 million for security improvements at Naval Weapons Station
Earle, $1.16 million for an instrument landing system at Newark International
Airport and more than $17 million to rebuild New Jersey beaches.
</P>
<P>
	   The list goes on. These are the projects that New Jersey lawmakers -
Republicans and Democrats alike - boast about when discussing what they have
done for their districts.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain defines pork as "low-priority, unnecessary, or wasteful spending" on
projects that have not be reviewed in a competitive process. His web site
includes the caveat that McCain's criticism is "not intended to reflect a
judgment on the merits of an item."
</P>
<P>
	   Asked last week about McCain's ideas on pork, two of his leading New Jersey
supporters offered different assessments.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think he's wrong in what he considers pork," said lobbyist Hazel Gluck.
"And when he gets to be president of the United States I think that will
change."
</P>
<P>
	   She continued: "Pork to me is giving money for some project that doesn't
mean anything to anybody. I don't consider replenishing the beaches as pork. I
personally think we look better if we look at the defense department spending
100 bucks for a toilet seat."
</P>
<P>
	   Schluter, R-Mercer, thinks of himself as a McCain-like maverick in the New
Jersey Legislature. He said he agrees with McCain - in theory.
</P>
<P>
	   But in practice, he said, even pork opponents have to grab their share until
the entire system changes.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you don't play by the rules of the system you can get left in the dust,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain may feel the same. Last month, an anti-pork coalition in Washington
gave him only average grades in steering clear of wasteful spending projects
that come before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   "McCain talks the talk, but when it comes time for leadership, he walks,"
said Courtney Cuff of Friends of the Earth, one of the organizations in the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain spokeswoman Nancy Ives replied that for 17 years McCain has "fought
against pork-barrel spending items in every appropriations bill."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1240 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Trade Meeting Seeks Healing  </HEADLINE>
    By PATRICK McDOWELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The breakdown of last year's world trade talks in
Seattle into street violence and bitter disagreement may be partly healed by an
upcoming gathering in Bangkok, a U.N. trade leader said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.N. Conference on Trade and Development will gather representatives of
some 180 countries in a meeting to try to bridge gaps between poor and rich
nations.
</P>
<P>
	   Those gaps led to the World Trade Organization's failure in November to
launch a new round of trade negotiations. The Seattle talks ended up foundering
amid chaotic street violence and demonstrations against the theme of
globalization that President Clinton and some other leaders were encouraging.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubens Ricupero, the Brazilian secretary-general of the U.N. conference,
called UNCTAD, told a news conference he has detected a fresh spirit of
compromise since then that might help push the world trade agenda forward.
</P>
<P>
	   UNCTAD holds its conference every four years. This year's meeting, in the
Thai capital from Feb. 12-19, will be preceded by a forum for activist groups
starting Monday. That gathering will try to keep disagreements in the debating
halls and off the streets.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are confident that in our conference, there will be what we could call a
healing process after Seattle," Ricupero said. "We are beginning to see some
signs in the world after Seattle that people are willing to make some
compromises."
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike the WTO, which hammers out international trade treaties and has the
power to enforce them, UNCTAD is largely a discussion group concerned with how
trade can advance development in poor countries. But given that both
Geneva-based organizations deal with many of the same issues and people, hopes
are high that new stances may be found on disputes that helped sink the Seattle
meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the thorniest are agricultural export subsidies and the high tariff
barriers that rich nations employ to offset developing countries' price
advantages in exporting food and clothing. Those policies are a "major
distortion" of free trade, Ricupero said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricupero said Asia's rebound from financial crisis would be a prime topic at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The crisis ended more quickly than anyone expected, thanks to the strengths
that led to the continent's extraordinary growth in the first place, he said. He
cited World Bank predictions that Asian economies will average 4 percent growth
this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Given that UNCTAD deals mainly with developing countries' concerns, the U.S.
and many wealthier nations are sending development and trade officials, not
high-profile leaders. The only leader of one of the world's seven most
industrialized countries to attend will be Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, security at the conference will be tight. Shaken by a pair of
recent hostage seizures by radical Myanmar student dissidents, Thailand is
deploying more than 6,000 police officers backed up by helicopters, a bomb
squad, police dogs and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
	   Only a symbolic few protesters will be allowed near the Queen Sirikit
Conference Center. Other demonstrations will be confined to a park in central
Bangkok more than a mile away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1253 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Meeting May Bridge Gaps  </HEADLINE>
    By PATRICK McDOWELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
