<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police commanders feel pressure to keep crime numbers low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Crime is down in cities nationwide and the unwritten
mantra of the police brass is: It better stay that way. But some criminologists
feel that motto can lead to trouble.
<P>
	   Police commanders are under pressure from their superiors' expectations, and
some have doctored statistics to show the number of offenses still going down.
Other commanders allege they were transferred when their precincts showed an
increase in crime.
</P>
<P>
	   In January, two New York captains were transferred, and the captains' union
says the moves were prompted by a jump in the number of crimes. In 1998, the
head of the police transportation bureau was forced to resign after he was
accused of underreporting subway offenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Such problems are not unique to New York City. The Philadelphia police
department has come under fire for allegedly reporting major crimes as minor
ones. Police in Boca Raton, Fla., and Atlanta also have been accused of
doctoring statistics.
</P>
<P>
	   Commanders have always been held accountable for what goes on in their
precincts, but in the 1990s a program known in some departments as COMPSTAT -
which uses computerized statistics to more accurately outline crime patterns -
began to put commanders on the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
	   Criminologists say, however, that COMPSTAT is not to blame. They maintain
the problem arises because police brass put too much weight on the statistics,
without looking at the broader picture.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've often used the term criminal justice limbo stick - how low can you
go?" said James Alan Fox, a criminal justice professor at Northeastern
University.
</P>
<P>
	   "Can we hold someone accountable because you can't go lower, and the only
way left to go is up?," Fox added. "Holding a commander accountable purely
because the crime number increased, especially after falling for many years in a
row is shortsighted and unfair."
</P>
<P>
	   Alfred Blumstein, a criminologist at Carnegie Mellon University, agrees.
</P>
<P>
	   "You can't fire everybody," he said. "You have to understand what some of
the external factors are - which are under the control of the precinct commander
and ... which are not."
</P>
<P>
	   Former New York City Police Commissioner William Bratton, who introduced
COMPSTAT in the city, said if commanders were being transferred solely on the
basis of an increase in crime statistics, that was wrong.
</P>
<P>
	   "Despite our best efforts and best people, sometimes crime is going to go
up," said Bratton, commissioner from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   New York City police Capt. John F. Driscoll, who heads the Captains
Endowment Association - the union for police captains - said a person cannot
judge the effectiveness of a commanding officer by crime statistics alone.
</P>
<P>
	   "You have to take into account a commander's supervisory skills,
administrative skills, relationships with his cops and command, and more
importantly, his relationship with the community," Driscoll said.
</P>
<P>
	   Driscoll has criticized what he claims is the New York police practice of
transferring commanders when crime rises in their precincts. In the past few
weeks, Capt. James Guida of the 88th Precinct in Brooklyn and Capt. Joseph W.
Byrne of the 104th Precinct in Queens were transferred after statistics showed
an increase in crimes in their commands.
</P>
<P>
	   Police Commission Howard Safir denies Driscoll's allegations. "When I look
at whether or not to transfer a precinct commander, I look at the totality of
his performance," Safir said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Crime reduction is, of course, a very important factor, but community
relations is a very important factor, civilian complaints are a very important
factor. Precinct morale is a factor. Nobody gets transferred based strictly on
one thing."
</P>
<P>
	   Guida replaced Capt. Charles F. Dowd when auditors found in 1988 that Dowd
had underreported crimes by classifying felonies as misdemeanors. Dowd was
transferred instead of being fired because officials said he had not willfully
deceived the department.
</P>
<P>
	   Also in 1998, the head of the Police Transportation Bureau, Chief Kenneth
Donohue, resigned after he was accused of underreporting subway crime. Earlier
that year, Safir said subway crime had been underreported for decades by as much
as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Many crimes committed on trains or in stations were recorded as having
occurred above ground, he said, adding that the error was discovered during an
audit.
</P>
<P>
	   Other departments have seen similar problems. In 1998, the Philadelphia
police department came under fire when it was revealed that reports were being
rewritten to exclude key facts and that major offenses were being recast as
minor ones. The allegations prompted an inquiry by the FBI, and the city had to
withdraw its crime figures from the FBI for 1996, 1997 and part of 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1997, Atlanta Deputy Police Chief Louis Arcangeli alleged that the
department's 1996 crime statistics were softened by writing off some unsolved
crimes and misclassifying some violent crimes as non-violent.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard claimed a state audit
exonerated his department of any wrongdoing, but the audit included an FBI
finding a significant number of robberies, rapes and car thefts were incorrectly
listed as unfounded.
</P>
<P>
	   Arcangeli has since been demoted to captain, but Harvard denied this was
because of his allegations. Arcangeli continues to work for the department and
said in a recent telephone interview that police commanders are now vigilant
about reporting crimes because the state is monitoring the department.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, Attorney General Janet Reno ordered an informal inquiry into the
Boca Raton, Fla., police department to see if officers downgraded hundreds of
crimes to enhance the city's image as a safe place to live. The scandal cost
Police Chief Peter Petracco and the department's No. 3 ranking officer their
jobs. The department allegedly downgraded burglaries and petty thefts to the
point where they did not need to be included in the city's annual report to the
state and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
	   Mary Victoria Pyne, unit chief with the Uniformed Crime Reporting Program
managed by the FBI, said the federal government scrutinizes crime data from
17,000 law enforcement agencies, making it hard for police officers doctoring
statistics to get away with it.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are not seeing a lot of inaccurate statistics," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bratton also said that COMPSTAT makes it nearly impossible to fudge
statistics without it eventually being uncovered.
</P>
<P>
	   "COMPSTAT is about transparency. You have to come out and show your peers
what you've done," he said. "If crime is way down in your precinct, your
colleagues will ask you how you did that, and you'll have to answer. There's
nowhere to hide."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
