<HEADLINE> Latest poll says candidates remain neck and neck  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A new poll released Sunday on the U.S. Senate race finds
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in a statistical dead heat,
but with a majority expecting Giuliani to eventually win.
<P>
	   The survey by the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute shows Giuliani with a
45 to 42 percent lead over Clinton, but the difference disappears once the
3-point margin of error is figured in.
</P>
<P>
	   Ten percent of those surveyed were undecided.
</P>
<P>
	   But fully half of those polled - including some Clinton supporters - expect
the mayor to win. Only 31 percent expect Clinton to win.
</P>
<P>
	   Female voters of all races were about equally split between the two groups,
but white women prefer the mayor, 52 to 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The survey also found that Giuliani is regarded as more knowledgeable about
state issues, while Clinton is regarded as having a more suitable personality
for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   Seventy-three percent of those surveyed said the mayor understands the
issues and problems facing New York State, but only 42 percent say the same of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   And while 70 percent think Clinton has the personality to be an effective
U.S. Senator, only 58 percent believe Giuliani does.
</P>
<P>
	   More than seven in 10 voters rated both of them high on leadership and
intelligence, although people gave Giuliani slightly higher marks for leadership
and her slightly higher marks for brains.
</P>
<P>
	   And a month after Clinton moved into her new Westchester home in Chappaqua,
46 percent still say that it bothers them that she's not from New York, compared
to 54 percent who say that it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
	   A Quinnipiac survey taken a year ago showed Clinton leading Giuliani 54-36,
with 57 percent saying they expected the mayor would ultimately win.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Clinton and Giuliani were given favorable ratings by a little more than
a third of those polled. That's a few points lower for Giuliani since January,
but Clinton's best favorability rating since June.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton was to formally announce her candidacy Sunday while Giuliani got his
share of the media's attention with appearances on five TV talk shows.
</P>
<P>
	   "Today's big show by First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton may cause a thaw, but
so far the Senate race seems frozen, with Mayor Giuliani holding on the high
side of a squeaker," Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll surveyed 1,072 registered voters by phone from Feb. 2 to 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1341 </TRAILER>
