<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton announces Senate candidacy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) - With the president taking a step back from the
spotlight, Hillary Rodham Clinton, her family at her side, planned to go before
2,000 people Sunday to announce her Senate candidacy from a state she has called
home for only a month.
<P>
	   The race for the seat being vacated by fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick
Moynihan is expected to pit Clinton against Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican
mayor of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   No other first lady has ever run for public office and in doing so, Clinton
steps out of the long and scandal-scarred shadow of her husband. Bill Clinton is
said to be one of her major advisers as she resumes the career she put aside to
help him capture the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton, daughter Chelsea and mother Dorothy Rodham assembled in
this New York City suburb to be with the first lady for her formal campaign
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
	   There is little real doubt that Clinton will face Giuliani in the polls, but
the mayor has not held his own formal campaign announcement. About the closest
he's come was on ABC's "This Week," one of five TV talk shows he appeared on
Sunday. When asked if he planned to run, he said, "Looks that way."
</P>
<P>
	   Recent polls have shown Giuliani with a slight lead over Clinton and running
even with her among women voters. That's a far cry from a year ago when talk was
fresh about a possible Clinton campaign that many doubted would ever come to
pass. Sympathy was strong from the Monica Lewinsky scandal and polls showed her
well ahead of the mayor if she did run.
</P>
<P>
	   Five months later, she formed a Senate committee and began raising money for
the race. At Moynihan's sprawling farm on a bright July day she kicked off a
summer-long "listening tour" of the state that bled over into the fall and took
her from Broadway to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
	   "Now I suppose the questions on everyone's mind is why the Senate and why
New York and why me?" she said at the farm. "All I can say is that I care deeply
about the issues that are important in this state that I have already been
learning about and hearing about."
</P>
<P>
	   By December, she was assuring supporters she intended to run. In early
January, she moved into a $1.7 million house in suburban Westchester County just
north of New York City to establish residency in the state she had decided to
adopt. President Clinton said he would move there when he left the White House
at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
	   For her formal announcement, Clinton chose a gymnasium at the State
University of New York at Purchase not far from her new home, a gym that serves
as the practice court for the New York Knicks basketball team.
</P>
<P>
	   Other than a closeness to home, political experts said there was good reason
for Clinton to stage her announcement in Westchester.
</P>
<P>
	   "When duck hunting, one goes where the ducks are," Republican consultant Jay
Severin explained. "The independent suburban ducks are the ducks in this
campaign that are yet to be bagged."
</P>
<P>
	   In statewide races, suburban voters from Westchester County and Long Island
are considered a key to success and a Marist College poll released Friday showed
Giuliani leading in the suburbs, 56 percent to 34 percent, his strongest showing
in any region of the state.
</P>
<P>
	   While Giuliani dismissed the Clinton announcement as "a Hollywood type of
thing," a top Democratic strategist not connected to the Clinton campaign said
it served a real purpose, especially for a famous out-of-towner still viewed
skeptically by many New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
	   "It makes people understand this is for real and not a joke. It's not a game
anymore," Hank Sheinkopf said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton campaign arranged for about 500 house parties to be held
simultaneously around the state for more than 20,000 supporters who would watch
the announcement on television and then listen in on a conference telephone call
from the candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Clinton was to fly to Buffalo to begin a tour across the state
that would take her to Rochester on Tuesday, Syracuse on Wednesday and Albany on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   As of the end of the year, she had raised $8 million and Giuliani, who
started fund raising three months earlier, had raised almost $12 million. It is
expected to be the most expensive Senate race in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
	   In seeking to replace Moynihan in the Senate, Clinton hopes to make another
kind of history. No woman has ever been independently elected to statewide
office in New York. Former vice presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro
unsuccessfully sought the Democratic Senate nomination in 1992 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's terrific," Ferraro said. "I think it's taking the role of the
first lady and putting it in the perspective of the 21st century ... We now know
that there is an afterlife for these women as well as being an assistant or
whatever in the White House."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
