<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The 'other' Carnegie Hall brings music, art to West Virginia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LEWISBURG, W.Va. (AP) - The name "Carnegie Hall" conjures up
superlatives, a place where only the best perform.
<P>
	   It also conjures up New York.
</P>
<P>
	   But there are two other Carnegie Halls, also built with money from steel
baron Andrew Carnegie and used to present quality arts to their communities.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides New York and Carnegie's hometown of Dunfermline, Scotland, there is
Lewisburg, where this four-story Georgian Revival Carnegie Hall sits just a bit
off the beaten path.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're the humble stepsister," says Vivian Conly, executive director in
Lewisburg.
</P>
<P>
	   Once the richest man in the world, Carnegie gave away millions of his vast
fortune to fund libraries. And while many of those have music halls, including
the one in Pittsburgh, Carnegie seldom donated money to fund places solely
devoted to music and the performing arts.
</P>
<P>
	   The spacious New York hall can seat thousands; Lewisburg, which cost $33,000
in 1902, can hold only 400. And where gracefully curved tiered seating and plush
carpet add to the New York hall's luxury, dark red plaster walls and teal
leather seats help hide imperfections in Lewisburg.
</P>
<P>
	   Because it was built for the Lewisburg Female Institute, which later became
the Greenbrier College for Women, "it's institutional rather than elegant and
grand," Conly says.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, patrons and performers seem to enjoy the intimate setting, where
paintings by local artists grace the lobby and a hand-carved staircase leads to
the balcony above.
</P>
<P>
	   The red brick building also houses art and dance studios, a small museum and
meeting rooms. A kitchen is used for culinary classes, while several other rooms
are used for weaving, pottery, basket-making and glass art. Skills learned in
class are seen in a vibrant mosaic that covers a once drab wall.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Carnegie built his fortune as a steel tycoon in neighboring
Pennsylvania, he had no connection to West Virginia. He was persuaded by James
Lang, chairman of the Board of Trustees of the women's college, to donate money
to replace a structure destroyed by fire.
</P>
<P>
	   The men shared the same Scottish roots.
</P>
<P>
	   That simple connection produced a place that brings the arts to southern
West Virginia, with live performances by artists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., who with his own wealthy family has been a
staunch supporter of the arts, called the Lewisburg hall a "wonderful asset."
</P>
<P>
	   "It may not have the same stature as its New York cousin, but as far as I'm
concerned, it's the jewel of the Carnegie Hall family," Rockefeller says.
</P>
<P>
	   Carnegie Hall lay dormant for years after the women's college closed in
1972. For several years it was used as a mental hospital. But when the once
stately building was about to be condemned in 1983, local residents formed a
nonprofit group to save it.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1995, in the midst of a nearly $3 million renovation project, the
National Endowment for the Arts recognized the Lewisburg hall as a model for
rural arts agency management and arts education.
</P>
<P>
	   And two years later, it was chosen for inclusion in The John F. Kennedy
Performing Arts Center and Schools' Partners in Education program.
</P>
<P>
	   "Carnegie Hall," Conly says, "is one of West Virginia's greatest treasures."
</P>
<P>
	   Celebrated violinist Isaac Stern, the namesake of Carnegie Hall's main
auditorium in New York, played the West Virginia hall in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   Jazz trumpeter Wynton Marsalis, country and bluegrass star Ricky Skaggs and
blues artist Taj Mahal are among the many performers to take the stage here,
along with the Vienna Boys' Choir, the National Theater of the Deaf and the
Mystical Arts of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
	   The monks, who have shared stages with Phillip Glass, Paul Simon, Patti
Smith, Natalie Merchant and the Beastie Boys, spent a week in Lewisburg last
year.
</P>
<P>
	   This season, the Millennium Performance Series includes artists Angela Au,
who, at age 11, played piano for Queen Elizabeth II; Celtic Rhythm, a group of
Irish step dancers and musicians; and The Dillards, who appeared as the Darling
family on the "Andy Griffith Show" in the 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1350 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For Hillary Clinton the battle begins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) - For Hillary Rodham Clinton, Sunday's formal entry
into the New York Senate campaign is the first step down a very bumpy road that
can lead to her becoming a political force in her own right or a footnote in
history.
<P>
	   With most polls showing her likely Republican rival, New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, slightly ahead, "it is she who must change the fundamental
dynamics. She's got to shake things up," Republican consultant Jay Severin said.
</P>
<P>
	   "She needs to, as the political consultants say, get on message and generate
a little more enthusiasm from her base supporters," pollster Lee Miringoff, head
of Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion, said.
</P>
<P>
	   In a state where Democrats outnumber Republicans by an almost 5-3 margin,
Clinton not only finds herself trailing Giuliani overall, but with no advantage
among women voters.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, a Marist poll out Friday showed Giuliani leading Clinton among
white women, 52 percent to 34 percent. The poll also showed him taking 23
percent of Democratic voters while she landed just 12 percent of Republicans.
Among independent voters, Giuliani led Clinton, 57 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Not to worry, says former vice presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro, the
former congresswoman from Queens who twice unsuccessfully sought the Democratic
Senate nomination in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "Once people hear where he stands on issues that are important to us on a
federal level, it's a different ball game," Ferraro predicted. "Then, you will
see the Democratic voters running straight home to Hillary and you will see
women moving in great numbers into her column."
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Clinton's campaign strategy has been clear for months. At every
opportunity, she stresses the need for better schools, more affordable quality
health care, lower transportation costs and more job-creating programs. And, she
questions whether the often blunt Giuliani has the proper temperament to get
along and get things done in the collegial Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   "The mayor always gets angry about things," she said late last year during a
stop in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
	   "She's got to engage the mayor on issues that play for her," veteran
Republican operative Nelson Warfield said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anything that lets her get in the game and actually start trading blows
with this guy has got to be good for her," Warfield added.
</P>
<P>
	   But the GOP consultant, who is not involved in the Senate race, cautioned
that Clinton's task isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
	   "Every other contender who has ever gone up against Rudy Giuliani has tried
to bait him into making some sort of mistake," Warfield said. "But he's an
incredibly disciplined hothead, so he has largely avoided that fate. But she
will eventually attempt to pull it off."
</P>
<P>
	   On the other hand, Democratic consultant Hank Sheinkopf, who is also not
involved in the campaign, said Clinton's surrounding herself with family,
including President Clinton, at her campaign announcement Sunday was a smart
move.
</P>
<P>
	   "It shows she is a family person in spite of all the troubles they have
experienced," he said. "It makes her more human. It removes the sharp edges."
</P>
<P>
	   Sheinkopf said having President Clinton along could also be a big help for
her in heavily Democratic New York City where he remains highly popular and even
in the crucial suburbs of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
	   "He won Nassau County in '92 and '96," Sheinkopf recalled.
</P>
<P>
	   One issue still haunting Clinton is the carpetbagger charge. Until she moved
into a $1.7 million house in suburban Westchester County on Jan. 6 she had never
lived or worked in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   But the latest Marist poll found that for the first time since February of
last year, fewer than half the voters surveyed expressed concern that Clinton
lacked New York roots.
</P>
<P>
	   Forty-seven percent of voters said they were at least somewhat concerned
about Clinton not being from New York while 41 percent said they were not
concerned at all about that. In the Marist poll, the carpetbagger concern peaked
in December when 57 percent of voters said they were at least somewhat
concerned.
</P>
<P>
	   Miringoff said the bottom line in the Senate race is that while "Giuliani is
ahead, Clinton is within striking distance."
</P>
<P>
	   "She has to shore up her Democratic base and if she does that, she's fine,"
Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   Marc Humbert has covered New York politics for The Associated Press for more
than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1353 </TRAILER>
