<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton To Announce Candidacy  </HEADLINE>
   By MARC HUMBERT AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- With the president taking a step back from the
spotlight, Hillary Rodham Clinton planned to go before 2,000 people Sunday to
announce her Senate candidacy from a state she has called home for only a month.
</P>
<P>
	   The race for the seat being vacated by fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick
Moynihan is likely to pit Clinton against Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican mayor
of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   No other first lady has ever run for public office and in doing so, Clinton
steps out of the long and scandal-scarred shadow of her husband.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton, daughter Chelsea and mother Dorothy Rodham assembled in
this New York City suburb to be with the first lady for her formal campaign
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
	   Recent polls have shown Giuliani with a slight lead over Clinton and running
even with her among women voters. That's a far cry from a year ago when sympathy
was strong from the Monica Lewinsky scandal and polls showed her well ahead of
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
	   On Sunday morning talk shows, Giuliani reminded viewers of Clinton's late
arrival to New York politics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My record of success comes out of my knowledge, experience, background and
life experience as a lifetime resident of the state,'' he said on CBS' ``Face
the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``How is it that the Democratic Party can't come up with a candidate for the
Senate from the state of New York? What does that say about the Democratic
Party?''
</P>
<P>
	   Last July at Moynihan's sprawling farm, Clinton kicked off a summer-long
``listening tour'' of the state that extended into the fall and took her from
Broadway to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
	   By December, she was assuring supporters she intended to run. And in early
January, she moved into a $1.7 million house in suburban Westchester County just
north of New York City to establish residency.
</P>
<P>
	   For her formal announcement, Clinton chose the State University of New York
at Purchase not far from her new home. Political experts said there was good
reason to stage her announcement in Westchester.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When duck hunting, one goes where the ducks are,'' Republican consultant
Jay Severin said. ``The independent suburban ducks are the ducks in this
campaign that are yet to be bagged.''
</P>
<P>
	   In statewide races, suburban voters from Westchester County and Long Island
are considered a key to success. A Marist College poll released Friday showed
Giuliani leading in the suburbs, 56 percent to 34 percent, his strongest showing
in any region of the state.
</P>
<P>
	   While Giuliani dismissed the Clinton announcement as ``a Hollywood type of
thing,'' a top Democratic strategist not connected to the Clinton campaign said
it served a real purpose, especially for a famous out-of-towner still viewed
skeptically by many New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It makes people understand this is for real and not a joke. It's not a
game anymore,'' Hank Sheinkopf said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton campaign arranged for about 500 house parties to be held
simultaneously around the state so more than 20,000 supporters could watch the
announcement on television and then listen in on a conference telephone call
from the candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   As of the end of the year, Clinton had raised $8 million and Giuliani, who
started fund raising three months earlier, had raised almost $12 million. It is
expected to be the most expensive Senate race in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
	   In seeking to replace Moynihan in the Senate, Clinton hopes to make another
kind of history. No woman has ever been independently elected to statewide
office in New York. Former vice presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro
unsuccessfully sought the Democratic Senate nomination in 1992 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think it's terrific,'' Ferraro said. ``I think it's taking the role of
the first lady and putting it in the perspective of the 21st century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1356 </TRAILER>
