<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For spot movement Sun. Feb. 6 for Mon. Feb. 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - State legislators have embarked on a display of very
public angst if not outrage over one of the biggest spikes in home heating oil
prices ever in peacetime.
<P>
	   At hearings last week, lawmakers probed expert witnesses about the global
petroleum distribution system, the size of national oil reserves, the effects of
cold weather on prices and other aspects of a problem that, ultimately, they
probably cannot affect one whit.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's not a lot I think you can do to intercede in the system," said
Michael Trunzo, chief executive officer of the Empire State Petroleum
Association and son of longtime state Sen. Caesar Trunzo. "There really isn't
anything they can do."
</P>
<P>
	   A former energy analyst under Gov. Mario Cuomo agreed there's nothing state
government can do about the current price crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   But you wouldn't know it in Albany, where no less than two legislative
hearings were held last week on the oil price increase. The state Senate will
hold another hearing Monday on the same subject, and says it has more planned.
</P>
<P>
	   "While it may be viewed by some as good politics, it can also result in good
policy," state Sen. James Wright, a Jefferson County Republican, said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Richard Dollinger, D-Rochester, called the Legislature's gathering and
review of facts on the oil price spike "government at its finest."
</P>
<P>
	   Wright, chairman of the Senate Energy and Telecommunications Committee, will
be co-chairing the Legislature's third oil price hearing Monday with Republican
Sen. Charles Fuschillo, chairman of the Senate Consumer Protection Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   That's not to be confused with the joint oil price hearing in the Assembly
which was run by Energy Committee Chairman Paul Tonko, D-Amsterdam, and Audrey
Pheffer, D-Queens, chairwoman of the Assembly Consumer Affairs and Protection
Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Tonko said he suggested to Wright that the committees be combined to avoid
duplication of effort. Last week, four of the same witnesses testified before at
both the Assembly and Senate hearings.
</P>
<P>
	   Wright, however, said Senate and Assembly members from four committees would
be too unwieldy at one hearing. And besides, he said, the Senate's energy and
consumer protection committees were looking at the oil pricing problem
differently than the Assembly's energy and consumer affairs committees.
</P>
<P>
	   The sessions are shaping up along the lines of hearings in 1990, when prices
also jumped during another cold snap when supplies were low and utilities
temporarily switched large customers from natural gas to oil. Price gouging was
suspected then, too, but not proved. Trunzo said his testimony will mirror his
trade association's testimony in 1990,	   So why are lawmakers, who haven't
produced an on-time state budget since Ronald Reagan was president, taking on
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and the free market system?
Heating oil users are also voters.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, the typical home heating oil price is starting to drop a few
pennies a gallon last week, according to the Empire State Petroleum Association.
The average price apparently peaked around Jan. 24 at about $1.67 a gallon -
compared to $1.19 on Jan. 10 and 90 cents a gallon in the fall. But competition
prompted retailers to absorb some of the wholesale price increase that doubled
over 14 days in January, according to the association.
</P>
<P>
	   The political outrage from New York officials so far hasn't seemed to light
a fire in Washington, or with OPEC.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. George Pataki a week ago said the Clinton administration response to
requests for help was inadequate. New York has 1.4 million poor people who could
get federal money to pay fuel bills and Pataki had sought between $35 million
and $40 million in emergency aid. Instead, New York got $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki, GOP Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, Democratic U.S. Sen.
Charles Schumer and others also called on Washington to release some of the
nation's oil reserves to help offset the high fuel prices, but U.S. Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson rejected that plea.
</P>
<P>
	   So the hearings continue to seek answers to why this crisis happened, what
can be done about it and how a repeat be can avoided.
</P>
<P>
	   In testimony in both hearings last week, the president of the state Energy
Research and Development Authority indicated there may not be much government
can do about a price spike in a free market. William Valentino's recommendation:
"We should continue to investigate and study the situation."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
