<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For Hillary Clinton the battle begins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) - For Hillary Rodham Clinton, Sunday's formal entry
into the New York Senate campaign is the first step down a very bumpy road that
can lead to her becoming a political force in her own right or a footnote in
history.
<P>
	   With most polls showing her likely Republican rival, New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, slightly ahead, "it is she who must change the fundamental
dynamics. She's got to shake things up," Republican consultant Jay Severin said.
</P>
<P>
	   "She needs to, as the political consultants say, get on message and generate
a little more enthusiasm from her base supporters," pollster Lee Miringoff, head
of Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion, said.
</P>
<P>
	   In a state where Democrats outnumber Republicans by an almost 5-3 margin,
Clinton not only finds herself trailing Giuliani overall, but with no advantage
among women voters.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, a Marist poll out Friday showed Giuliani leading Clinton among
white women, 52 percent to 34 percent. The poll also showed him taking 23
percent of Democratic voters while she landed just 12 percent of Republicans.
Among independent voters, Giuliani led Clinton, 57 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Not to worry, says former vice presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro, the
former congresswoman from Queens who twice unsuccessfully sought the Democratic
Senate nomination in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "Once people hear where he stands on issues that are important to us on a
federal level, it's a different ball game," Ferraro predicted. "Then, you will
see the Democratic voters running straight home to Hillary and you will see
women moving in great numbers into her column."
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Clinton's campaign strategy has been clear for months. At every
opportunity, she stresses the need for better schools, more affordable quality
health care, lower transportation costs and more job-creating programs. And, she
questions whether the often blunt Giuliani has the proper temperament to get
along and get things done in the collegial Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   "The mayor always gets angry about things," she said late last year during a
stop in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
	   "She's got to engage the mayor on issues that play for her," veteran
Republican operative Nelson Warfield said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anything that lets her get in the game and actually start trading blows
with this guy has got to be good for her," Warfield added.
</P>
<P>
	   But the GOP consultant, who is not involved in the Senate race, cautioned
that Clinton's task isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
	   "Every other contender who has ever gone up against Rudy Giuliani has tried
to bait him into making some sort of mistake," Warfield said. "But he's an
incredibly disciplined hothead, so he has largely avoided that fate. But she
will eventually attempt to pull it off."
</P>
<P>
	   On the other hand, Democratic consultant Hank Sheinkopf, who is also not
involved in the campaign, said Clinton's surrounding herself with family,
including President Clinton, at her campaign announcement Sunday was a smart
move.
</P>
<P>
	   "It shows she is a family person in spite of all the troubles they have
experienced," he said. "It makes her more human. It removes the sharp edges."
</P>
<P>
	   Sheinkopf said having President Clinton along could also be a big help for
her in heavily Democratic New York City where he remains highly popular and even
in the crucial suburbs of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
	   "He won Nassau County in '92 and '96," Sheinkopf recalled.
</P>
<P>
	   One issue still haunting Clinton is the carpetbagger charge. Until she moved
into a $1.7 million house in suburban Westchester County on Jan. 6 she had never
lived or worked in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   But the latest Marist poll found that for the first time since February of
last year, fewer than half the voters surveyed expressed concern that Clinton
lacked New York roots.
</P>
<P>
	   Forty-seven percent of voters said they were at least somewhat concerned
about Clinton not being from New York while 41 percent said they were not
concerned at all about that. In the Marist poll, the carpetbagger concern peaked
in December when 57 percent of voters said they were at least somewhat
concerned.
</P>
<P>
	   Miringoff said the bottom line in the Senate race is that while "Giuliani is
ahead, Clinton is within striking distance."
</P>
<P>
	   "She has to shore up her Democratic base and if she does that, she's fine,"
Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   Marc Humbert has covered New York politics for The Associated Press for more
than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
