<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The 'other' Carnegie Hall brings music, art to West Virginia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LEWISBURG, W.Va. (AP) - The name "Carnegie Hall" conjures up
superlatives, a place where only the best perform.
<P>
	   It also conjures up New York.
</P>
<P>
	   But there are two other Carnegie Halls, also built with money from steel
baron Andrew Carnegie and used to present quality arts to their communities.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides New York and Carnegie's hometown of Dunfermline, Scotland, there is
Lewisburg, where this four-story Georgian Revival Carnegie Hall sits just a bit
off the beaten path.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're the humble stepsister," says Vivian Conly, executive director in
Lewisburg.
</P>
<P>
	   Once the richest man in the world, Carnegie gave away millions of his vast
fortune to fund libraries. And while many of those have music halls, including
the one in Pittsburgh, Carnegie seldom donated money to fund places solely
devoted to music and the performing arts.
</P>
<P>
	   The spacious New York hall can seat thousands; Lewisburg, which cost $33,000
in 1902, can hold only 400. And where gracefully curved tiered seating and plush
carpet add to the New York hall's luxury, dark red plaster walls and teal
leather seats help hide imperfections in Lewisburg.
</P>
<P>
	   Because it was built for the Lewisburg Female Institute, which later became
the Greenbrier College for Women, "it's institutional rather than elegant and
grand," Conly says.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, patrons and performers seem to enjoy the intimate setting, where
paintings by local artists grace the lobby and a hand-carved staircase leads to
the balcony above.
</P>
<P>
	   The red brick building also houses art and dance studios, a small museum and
meeting rooms. A kitchen is used for culinary classes, while several other rooms
are used for weaving, pottery, basket-making and glass art. Skills learned in
class are seen in a vibrant mosaic that covers a once drab wall.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Carnegie built his fortune as a steel tycoon in neighboring
Pennsylvania, he had no connection to West Virginia. He was persuaded by James
Lang, chairman of the Board of Trustees of the women's college, to donate money
to replace a structure destroyed by fire.
</P>
<P>
	   The men shared the same Scottish roots.
</P>
<P>
	   That simple connection produced a place that brings the arts to southern
West Virginia, with live performances by artists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., who with his own wealthy family has been a
staunch supporter of the arts, called the Lewisburg hall a "wonderful asset."
</P>
<P>
	   "It may not have the same stature as its New York cousin, but as far as I'm
concerned, it's the jewel of the Carnegie Hall family," Rockefeller says.
</P>
<P>
	   Carnegie Hall lay dormant for years after the women's college closed in
1972. For several years it was used as a mental hospital. But when the once
stately building was about to be condemned in 1983, local residents formed a
nonprofit group to save it.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1995, in the midst of a nearly $3 million renovation project, the
National Endowment for the Arts recognized the Lewisburg hall as a model for
rural arts agency management and arts education.
</P>
<P>
	   And two years later, it was chosen for inclusion in The John F. Kennedy
Performing Arts Center and Schools' Partners in Education program.
</P>
<P>
	   "Carnegie Hall," Conly says, "is one of West Virginia's greatest treasures."
</P>
<P>
	   Celebrated violinist Isaac Stern, the namesake of Carnegie Hall's main
auditorium in New York, played the West Virginia hall in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   Jazz trumpeter Wynton Marsalis, country and bluegrass star Ricky Skaggs and
blues artist Taj Mahal are among the many performers to take the stage here,
along with the Vienna Boys' Choir, the National Theater of the Deaf and the
Mystical Arts of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
	   The monks, who have shared stages with Phillip Glass, Paul Simon, Patti
Smith, Natalie Merchant and the Beastie Boys, spent a week in Lewisburg last
year.
</P>
<P>
	   This season, the Millennium Performance Series includes artists Angela Au,
who, at age 11, played piano for Queen Elizabeth II; Celtic Rhythm, a group of
Irish step dancers and musicians; and The Dillards, who appeared as the Darling
family on the "Andy Griffith Show" in the 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1406 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecution case to conclude with Diallo autopsy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - One of the 19 bullets pierced Amadou Diallo's aorta,
left lung and spine. Another tunneled through his liver and right lung. Others
broke his arm and leg.
<P>
	   A medical examiner is expected to present those findings and others in
gruesome detail at the close of the prosecution case against four police
officers accused of murdering the 22-year-old street vendor on his Bronx
doorstep. The official could testify by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Nineteen of the 41 bullets that the defendants fired at Diallo on Feb. 4,
1999, struck him. An autopsy found that one went into his right leg, traveled
upward and lodged behind his right knee - a route that could help prove
prosecutor Eric Warner's claim last week in opening statements that the officers
kept pulling their triggers after the West African immigrant "was falling down
or actually on the ground."
</P>
<P>
	   Kenneth Boss, 28; Sean Carroll, 36; Edward McMellon, 27; and Richard Murphy,
27, have pleaded innocent to the second-degree murder charges. If convicted,
they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The killing of an unarmed black man by four white officers produced a flood
of pretrial publicity and protests alleging widespread abuse of minorities by
police. An appeals court responded by moving the case to Albany, where it is
being televised.
</P>
<P>
	   The plain clothes officers allegedly made a "conscious decision" to kill
Diallo. Without warning, they cornered him in the vestibule of his two-story
apartment house and opened fire, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
	   But defense attorneys argue the shooting was a tragic - but justified -
mistake made while their clients searched Diallo's neighborhood for dangerous
suspects. They contend the victim caused a chain reaction by not heeding orders
to stop and suddenly pulling out a black wallet that, because of darkness,
appeared to be a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial, once expected to last a month or longer, is moving quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first two days, the jury - four black women, two white women and six
white men - heard from police and other witnesses who described the spot where
Diallo died as well lighted. One of Diallo's neighbors, Debbie Rivera, also
testified that she heard a volley of gunfire followed by a brief pause, then a
longer, final volley.
</P>
<P>
	   Another neighbor, a police recruit named Thomas Bell, reportedly will
testify this week that he also heard a pause. The testimony of Rivera and Bell
could be used to argue the officers had a clear chance to cease fire.
</P>
<P>
	   But in a defense case that should begin this week, attorneys hope to portray
the neighbors as unreliable. They plan to call a sergeant who interviewed Rivera
on the night of the shooting. His report says she heard one continuous burst.
</P>
<P>
	   Other defense witnesses include a paramedic who used a flashlight to view
Diallo's body in a vestibule because, attorneys say, the lighting was so poor.
Also, Murphy's attorney, James Culleton, told jurors they would hear from
someone who will "tell you that (Diallo) was acting suspicious, peeking in and
out of this vestibule" moments before the officers rolled up in an unmarked car.
</P>
<P>
	   The centerpiece of the defense case will be the officers themselves. All
four have said they want to take the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
	   "You will hear from Ken Boss," the officer's attorney, Steven Brounstein,
told jurors. "And what I will ask you to do is step inside his shoes and try to
view what he viewed and hear what he heard that night. When you do that, you
will find in your heart and your head that his conduct was justified."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1410 </TRAILER>
