<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecution case to conclude with Diallo autopsy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - One of the 19 bullets pierced Amadou Diallo's aorta,
left lung and spine. Another tunneled through his liver and right lung. Others
broke his arm and leg.
<P>
	   A medical examiner is expected to present those findings and others in
gruesome detail at the close of the prosecution case against four police
officers accused of murdering the 22-year-old street vendor on his Bronx
doorstep. The official could testify by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Nineteen of the 41 bullets that the defendants fired at Diallo on Feb. 4,
1999, struck him. An autopsy found that one went into his right leg, traveled
upward and lodged behind his right knee - a route that could help prove
prosecutor Eric Warner's claim last week in opening statements that the officers
kept pulling their triggers after the West African immigrant "was falling down
or actually on the ground."
</P>
<P>
	   Kenneth Boss, 28; Sean Carroll, 36; Edward McMellon, 27; and Richard Murphy,
27, have pleaded innocent to the second-degree murder charges. If convicted,
they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The killing of an unarmed black man by four white officers produced a flood
of pretrial publicity and protests alleging widespread abuse of minorities by
police. An appeals court responded by moving the case to Albany, where it is
being televised.
</P>
<P>
	   The plain clothes officers allegedly made a "conscious decision" to kill
Diallo. Without warning, they cornered him in the vestibule of his two-story
apartment house and opened fire, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
	   But defense attorneys argue the shooting was a tragic - but justified -
mistake made while their clients searched Diallo's neighborhood for dangerous
suspects. They contend the victim caused a chain reaction by not heeding orders
to stop and suddenly pulling out a black wallet that, because of darkness,
appeared to be a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial, once expected to last a month or longer, is moving quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first two days, the jury - four black women, two white women and six
white men - heard from police and other witnesses who described the spot where
Diallo died as well lighted. One of Diallo's neighbors, Debbie Rivera, also
testified that she heard a volley of gunfire followed by a brief pause, then a
longer, final volley.
</P>
<P>
	   Another neighbor, a police recruit named Thomas Bell, reportedly will
testify this week that he also heard a pause. The testimony of Rivera and Bell
could be used to argue the officers had a clear chance to cease fire.
</P>
<P>
	   But in a defense case that should begin this week, attorneys hope to portray
the neighbors as unreliable. They plan to call a sergeant who interviewed Rivera
on the night of the shooting. His report says she heard one continuous burst.
</P>
<P>
	   Other defense witnesses include a paramedic who used a flashlight to view
Diallo's body in a vestibule because, attorneys say, the lighting was so poor.
Also, Murphy's attorney, James Culleton, told jurors they would hear from
someone who will "tell you that (Diallo) was acting suspicious, peeking in and
out of this vestibule" moments before the officers rolled up in an unmarked car.
</P>
<P>
	   The centerpiece of the defense case will be the officers themselves. All
four have said they want to take the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
	   "You will hear from Ken Boss," the officer's attorney, Steven Brounstein,
told jurors. "And what I will ask you to do is step inside his shoes and try to
view what he viewed and hear what he heard that night. When you do that, you
will find in your heart and your head that his conduct was justified."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1459 </TRAILER>
