<HEADLINE> Giuliani Makes Talk Show Rounds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton wasn't the only New York politician
caught on camera Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Her unannounced GOP Senate rival, Rudolph Giuliani, found time to appear on
all five morning talk shows, discussing the race in depth but not officially
declaring his own candidacy for the seat held by retiring Democrat Daniel
Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In 1989, when I ran for mayor, I announced, I lost,'' he said on ``Fox
News Sunday.'' ``In 1993, when I didn't announce ... I won the election.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``So in '97, I decided not to announce and I won with the largest margin a
Republican has ever had in Democratic New York City,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani matched the appearances Attorney William Ginsburg made on ABC, CBS,
CNN, Fox and NBC on Feb. 1, 1998, as he defended his then-client, Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is it, folks,'' Ginsburg said on Fox that day. ``This is my last
round of Sunday shows. This thing has gotten out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ginsburg showed up on the talk show circuit two weeks later.
</P>
</TEXT>
