<HEADLINE> Forbes Campaigns in Delaware  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMYRNA, Del. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes portrayed
himself Sunday as a Washington outsider not beholden to special interests as he
campaigned in advance of the state's GOP primary next week.
</P>
<P>
	   At a town meeting at Smyrna fire hall, the millionaire magazine publisher
outlined for an audience of about 200 people his platform in favor of school
choice, a flat federal tax, a stronger military and his opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Washington politicians, the special interests, they don't have their
hooks into me,'' Forbes said to applause. ``If we got rid of the tax code, half
of the lobbyists would have to find a new line of work. I'm a compassionate guy,
and I would consider some retraining.''
</P>
<P>
	   He planned another town meeting Sunday evening in Newark.
</P>
<P>
	   Delaware Republicans gave Forbes his first primary victory in 1996, when he
was the sole contender to stump in the state. After placing a distant third in
New Hampshire with 13 percent of the vote last week, Forbes is looking to repeat
that win on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   But he must contend with Republican presidential front-runner George W.
Bush, who also has campaigned here. Sen. John McCain of Arizona has ignored
Delaware to focus on the GOP contest Feb. 19 in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   Tom Campbell, a consultant for a technology company from Clayton and a
registered Democrat, said afterward that he would vote for Forbes if he could.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think we need a businessman versus a lawyer to run this country as a
business,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nancy Koska of Smyrna, who brought her 11-year-old daughter Tracy, said she
had been debating between Forbes and McCain but that after hearing Forbes speak
she said she liked what he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He gave me some points to go back and look at McCain,'' Koska said. ``I
think Bush is too tied up with lobbyists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
