<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley to fight back in hope of rebounding  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Bruised by losses in Iowa and New Hampshire, Bill
Bradley's presidential campaign is fighting back against the aggressive campaign
being waged by rival Al Gore. Though the strategy is not entirely risk-free,
aides have concluded that Gore's tactics have left Bradley with little choice
but to respond.
<P>
	   "Part of our strategy will be drawing a contrast with the vice president,
which we will do increasingly," said Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking at a predominantly black church in Queens on Sunday to campaign
with activist Al Sharpton, Bradley said "I think I have to communicate better
with the Democratic base."
</P>
<P>
	   He wasted little time resuming his criticisms of Gore, which he had stepped
up in the closing days of the contest in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   Appearing earlier Sunday on NBC's "Meet the Press," the former New Jersey
senator renewed his attack on Gore's fund-raising practices in the last
campaign, criticizing the vice president's 1996 appearance at a Buddhist temple
near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think he has to explain more thoroughly what was happening at the
Buddhist temple, said Bradley. "If he didn't know it was a fund-raiser then he
was spectacularly naive."
</P>
<P>
	   He again warned that Republicans will hammer Gore with the issue in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no doubt in my mind that is going to happen," Bradley said. "This
is a real risk in the fall. The Democratic Party is taking a risk."
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley also has challenged Gore on health care and his record on abortion
and says voters want a "fresh start," a thinly veiled reference to President
Clinton's troubles.
</P>
<P>
	   "America is about competition, political campaigns are about competition,"
said Bradley, defending his assault. "If your positions are misrepresented, you
can only take it so long. That's the way I'll continue for the next four or five
weeks."
</P>
<P>
	   By then, the battle for the Democratic presidential nomination could well be
decided, with a high-stakes showdown in California, New York and other states on
March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   "California is the neutral ground," said Gore campaign spokesman Chris
Lehane.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have to take off on March 7," acknowledged Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   One place to begin is within his own party. Much of the Democratic
establishment is behind Gore and one of Bradley's most urgent tasks is winning
back key constituencies like blacks and women who surveys show overwhelmingly
support the vice president.
</P>
<P>
	   Both rivals took a breather over the weekend before launching an intense
burst of campaigning leading up to the big round of March 7 primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley opened his week in New York and was heading to Florida. Gore, too,
was beginning in New York, and both were setting aside ample time for
California.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have to win California," Bradley said. "I know I have some ground to make
up."
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also has focused heavily on California, and has the backing of key
state leaders like Gov. Gray Davis and organized labor. Polls give Gore the edge
there - a Field poll in mid-January had him ahead 44 percent to 17 percent - but
they can be unreliable as voters begin to tune in to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Countering Bradley, Gore's aides said they will continue the kind of
grassroots, retail campaign that led to success in the opening contests in Iowa
and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   "Al Gore is a national candidate," said Lehane, Gore's spokesman. "We'll be
campaigning in virtually every state where they have a primary. There's only one
candidate in this race who is undefeated and that's Al Gore."
</P>
<P>
	   For Bradley, the debate has been one of tactics. A core campaign theme has
been his argument that he's a nontraditional candidate who operates above the
charges and countercharges that have become staples of political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   But in the face of early setbacks, Bradley's approach has shifted. Backers
like Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska have urged Bradley - who picks up Secret
Service protection Monday - to be more aggressive and respond to Gore - and
that's becoming apparent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1555 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Maps Wreckage of Alaskan Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTINE HANLEY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORT HUENEME, Calif. (AP) -- Navy crews on Sunday mapped more of the ocean
floor near the crash site of Alaska Airlines Flight 261, leaving the plane's
wreckage alone but collecting some human remains.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Transportation Safety Board wants a detailed picture of the
aircraft debris before pieces of the plane are brought to the surface.
</P>
<P>
	   Exactly what will be brought up will depend on further interpretation of
flight data and cockpit voice recorders, which were still being analyzed in
Washington, an NTSB spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The ships have been out all night long,'' said Terry Williams. ``There's
more mapping that's going on. Naturally, in the process, if they find any bodies
or other remains they're bringing them up.''
</P>
<P>
	   The debris area is about 10 miles offshore in the Santa Barbara Channel,
covering an area about the size of a football field in water 640 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, more memorials were held for families and friends of the 88
people lost with the plane. Among them was a service by Cardinal Roger Mahony,
archbishop of Los Angeles, who led a service near Los Angeles International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
	   The Alaska Airlines MD-83 crashed a week ago, killing all 88 people on
board, during a flight from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, bound for San Francisco and
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane's voice recorder shows that for at least 30 minutes prior to the
crash the pilots were struggling to correct a problem with the tail-mounted
horizontal stabilizer, which they said had jammed.
</P>
<P>
	   Witnesses who saw the plane go down said it rolled upside down and spiraled
into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ventura County Medical Examiner's Office, which is responsible for
identifying the victims, has said that it has several nearly complete bodies.
Sheriff's spokesman Eric Nishimoto said it could be a week before any are
identified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1559 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some NJ SAVER checks not covering cost of 1999 tax increase  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Tax rebate checks mailed to New Jerseyans in
September were supposed to offset school tax increases for homeowners. But
published reports say the savings aren't adding up for a lot of the Garden
State's 566 municipalities, with the 1999 tax rates exceeding the amounts of the
checks.
<P>
	   Statewide, the rebates averaged $120. The average tax increase last year was
$135, according to the Star-Ledger of Newark, which cited data from the Office
of Legislative Services and the state Treasury Department in Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a tax cut but it was certainly a modest one. It's really kind of
laughable," Summit resident Bob Wolfenbarger told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfenbarger said he received a $76 rebate, which wasn't enough to cover the
$200 increase in 1999 property taxes on his home. But Wolfenbarger fared
slightly better than other homeowners in Summit, which got an average tax
increase of $399. Summit residents received the same amount in the rebate
program.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the program, which Governor Christie Whitman signed last April, the
rebate is calculated using the local 1997 school tax rate on the first $45,000
of a home's value. In that way, the amount each homeowner receives in a town is
the same.
</P>
<P>
	   "As my mother used to say, it's better than a sharp stick in the eye,"
Roosevelt resident Gayle Donnelly told the Gannett New Jersey bureau for
Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   Donnelly and her husband, David, said they recently sold their house in
Roosevelt because of the high taxes. Gayle Donnelly said the tax rebate the
couple received was $248, but also said the couple's school tax bill last year
amounted to more than $700.
</P>
<P>
	   The Star-Ledger reported 239 of the state's municipalities are paying more
than the statewide average increase of $135, the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman put the program to work amid hoopla, but also had asserted the
program wasn't meant to reduce property tax rates. Whitman instead urged local
governments and school districts to embrace structural change and reduce costs
through shared services, mergers and regionalization.
</P>
<P>
	   But critics maintain the state can do more. And the idea of merging doesn't
appeal to many.
</P>
<P>
	   Gannett New Jersey reported only 15 of the state's 566 municipalities have
applied for the $10 million Regional Efficiency Development Incentive program,
which was included in a $35 million package of bills Whitman signed at about the
time the tax rebate program was offered. The package was intended to encourage
local governments to share services.
</P>
<P>
	   In Roosevelt, for example, Mayor Michael Hamilton said residents have mixed
feelings about merging with other municipalities.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm willing to pay for it, even if I have to starve to death. It's a choice
and that's the way I feel," Roosevelt resident Sol Libsohn, 86, told Gannett.
</P>
<P>
	   Libsohn said although he would consider a merger under certain
circumstances, he like the borough the way it is.
</P>
<P>
	   Meantime, Whitman's proposed 2001 budget calls for boosting the statewide
average of the rebates to $240. But that wouldn't have kept up with the increase
in property taxes from 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   "Unless there is some dramatic change ... you're not going to be reducing
property taxes. You're just going to be reducing the rate of increase," said
Henry Coleman, director of Rutgers University's Center for Government Services.
</P>
<P>
	   Coleman said the state's total property tax bill has been increasing by $400
million to $500 million annually. The Star-Ledger reported the average 1999 tax
bill increased by 3.28 percent over the year previous, or from $4,109 to $4,244.
</P>
<P>
	   The New Jersey Policy Perspective, a think tank, recently issued a report
calling on the state to absorb 50 percent of local educational costs, increase
the state income tax, levy taxes on stocks and bonds, and expand NJ SAVER to
ease the tax bill for all property taxes, not just the school tax.
</P>
<P>
	   "The public's not getting the message that they are getting what the
governor argues is property tax relief. I think the issue remains a very, very
ripe one for the election in 2001," said Sen. Bernard Kenny, (D-Hudson). "The
property taxpayer is in no better shape than this."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1612 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
