<DOCNO> APW20000206.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Snow flurries crept across the Upper Midwest on Sunday, but most of the rest
of the nation was dry.
</P>
<P>
	   Clouds covered wide areas of the Upper Midwest and Ohio Valley as moisture
moved ahead of a low pressure system that was pushing through the Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
	   Light snow showers and flurries moved across southern Minnesota and northern
Iowa during the morning and spread eastward into southern Wisconsin and northern
Illinois during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the snow, a light mixture of rain and snow fell on parts of
southeastern Iowa.
</P>
<P>
	   On the West Coast, moist air flowing in from the Pacific Ocean produced a
few light showers in western sections of Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   The area of rain was expected to spread during the night, expanding into
northern and central California.
</P>
<P>
	   Farther inland, the moisture fueled isolated light snow showers in the
mountains of northern Idaho and western Montana.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere, a small area of isolated snow showers rolled across northern
Maine.
</P>
<P>
	   Sunday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a morning low
of 12 below zero at International Falls, Minn., to a midday reading of 74 at
Brownsville, Texas. The lowest wind chill was 41 below zero at Frenchville,
Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1612 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani hits talk show circuit ahead of Mrs. Clinton's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A few hours before first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
officially declared her candidacy for the U.S. Senate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
hit the political talk show circuit Sunday, saying he would probably run against
her.
<P>
	   Giuliani's comments - made during a series of national television interviews
- represent the closest he has come to saying he will run.
</P>
<P>
	   "May we assume that you wouldn't be running this Sunday morning gauntlet (of
talk shows) if you were not running?" asked Brit Hume on "Fox News Sunday."
</P>
<P>
	   "Ahhh, yes," the mayor said, momentarily hesitating.
</P>
<P>
	   When asked on ABC's "This Week" if he planned to run, Giuliani responded,
"Looks that way."
</P>
<P>
	   And on CNN's "Late Edition", he said: "Well, there's always doubt.
Otherwise, I might as well make some kind of Hollywood-style announcement of
some kind or other. But right now, it's very much a direction we're moving in.
We've raised over $12 million, we have over 90,000 donors."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani however, said he is unlikely to follow Mrs. Clinton's lead and
declare his candidacy in a grand way because he is superstitious about making
such pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
	   "In 1989, when I ran for mayor, I announced, I lost," he said on Fox. "In
1993, when I didn't announce, I forgot ... In 1997, I decided not to announce
and I won with the largest margin a Republican has ever won in Democratic New
York City. So I said to myself, 'You got to find a better way to do this then,
the big kind of announcement thing."'
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani added, "I have a very demanding full time job and the shorter I can
make this campaign, the better it's going to be ... I do have less time to
campaign (than Clinton)."
</P>
<P>
	   In all, Guiliani's whirlwind schedule Sunday morning took him to five
national political talk shows in about three hours as he scrambled to and from
midtown Manhattan television studios.
</P>
<P>
	   On ABC, he acknowledged that he and Clinton hold strikingly similar
positions on a number of issues - for example, both support abortion rights, the
death penalty, gun control, gay rights and welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are a lot of issues on which we agree," he said. "There are a lot of
issues in which we disagree. I think there's a fundamental difference ... I
believe in solutions that don't necessarily involve building larger government."
</P>
<P>
	   He said his campaign would focus on his success in reducing crime and
welfare and cutting taxes and was unlikely to bring up the Whitewater scandal as
a political issue.
</P>
<P>
	   "I doubt it, unless some relevant facts come out," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani also acknowledged that the line between his campaign and mayoral
staffs had blurred at times, but said the White House has aided Clinton as well.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's always going to be questions about overlap," he said on Fox. "Even
if somebody would argue with us, we've paid (from our campaign funds) for a lot
more."
</P>
<P>
	   Although Clinton has promised to serve her full six-year term if she is
elected, Giuliani refused to do the same.
</P>
<P>
	   And when asked whether he has the proper temperament for the U.S. Senate,
Giuliani said on "Meet the Press" that he had successfully worked with the
overwhelmingly Democratic City Council to pass budgets and other legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   "I tend to be a leader," he said. "I have strong ideas, I push very, very
hard for those ideas...We could use a Senator from New York who is a strong
advocate."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-06-00 1614 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Adopts Fighting Strategy  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bruised by losses in Iowa and New Hampshire, Bill Bradley's
presidential campaign is fighting back against the aggressive campaign being
waged by rival Al Gore. Though the strategy is not entirely risk-free, aides
have concluded that Gore's tactics have left Bradley with little choice but to
respond.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Part of our strategy will be drawing a contrast with the vice president,
which we will do increasingly,'' said Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Bradley wasted little time Sunday resuming his criticisms of Gore,
which he had stepped up in the closing days of the contest in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   Appearing on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' the former New Jersey senator renewed
his attack on Gore's fund-raising practices in the last campaign, criticizing
the vice president's 1996 appearance at a Buddhist temple near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think he has to explain more thoroughly what was happening at the
Buddhist temple, said Bradley. ``If he didn't know it was a fund-raiser then he
was spectacularly naive.''
</P>
<P>
	   He again warned that Republicans will hammer Gore with the issue in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is no doubt in my mind that is going to happen,'' Bradley said.
``This is a real risk in the fall. The Democratic Party is taking a risk.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley also has challenged Gore on health care and his record on abortion
and says voters want a ``fresh start,'' a thinly veiled reference to President
Clinton's troubles.
</P>
<P>
	   ``America is about competition, political campaigns are about competition,''
said Bradley, defending his assault. ``If your positions are misrepresented, you
can only take it so long. That's the way I'll continue for the next four or five
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
	   By then, the battle for the Democratic presidential nomination could well be
decided, with a high-stakes showdown in California, New York and other states on
March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   ``California is the neutral ground,'' said Gore campaign spokesman Chris
Lehane.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have to take off on March 7,'' acknowledged Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   One place to begin is within his own party. Much of the Democratic
establishment is behind Gore and one of Bradley's most urgent tasks is winning
back key constituencies like blacks and women who surveys show overwhelmingly
support the vice president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think I have to communicate better with the Democratic base,'' said
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   Looking to shore up that base, Bradley campaigned Sunday at Allen AME
Church, the state's largest black church, with activist Al Sharpton, who
proposed that the Democratic rivals debate in New York before a mostly black
audience.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley agreed, and aides said they would present the idea to Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am not taking the African-American vote for granted,'' said Bradley. ``I
have a lot of friends in New Work. We are building organizations in all the
March 7 states.''
</P>
<P>
	   Aides said Bradley would spend much of his campaign week on the issue of
race relations, heading to Florida to talk about affirmative action and South
Carolina to wade into the fight over the flying of the Confederate battle flag.
</P>
<P>
	   He noted that racial harmony was the topic of the first major speech he gave
as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's who I am, it's what I live,'' said Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   Both rivals took a breather over the weekend before launching an intense
burst of campaigning leading up to the big round of March 7 primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley opened his week in New York and was heading to Florida. Gore, too,
was beginning in New York, and both were setting aside ample time for
California.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have to win California,'' Bradley said. ``I know I have some ground to
make up.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also has focused heavily on California, and has the backing of key
state leaders like Gov. Gray Davis and organized labor. Polls give Gore the edge
there -- a Field poll in mid-January had him ahead 44 percent to 17 percent --
but they can be unreliable as voters begin to tune in to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Countering Bradley, Gore's aides said they will continue the kind of
grassroots, retail campaign that led to success in the opening contests in Iowa
and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Al Gore is a national candidate,'' said Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ``We'll
be campaigning in virtually every state where they have a primary. There's only
one candidate in this race who is undefeated and that's Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
	   For Bradley, the debate has been one of tactics. A core campaign theme has
been his argument that he's a nontraditional candidate who operates above the
charges and countercharges that have become staples of political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   But in the face of early setbacks, Bradley's approach has shifted. Backers
like Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska have urged Bradley -- who picks up Secret
Service protection Monday -- to be more aggressive and respond to Gore -- and
that's becoming apparent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1615 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Senate Candidacy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton on Sunday formally launched her
campaign for the U.S. Senate in a state she has called home for only a month.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am honored today to announce my candidacy for the U.S. Senate from New
York,'' she said as the crowd of 2,000 people in a gymnasium at a state
university campus in Purchase chanted ``Hillary! Hillary!''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I may be new to the neighborhood, but I'm not new to your concerns,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1615 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley to fight back in hope of rebounding  </HEADLINE>
