<DOCNO> APW20000206.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some NJ SAVER checks not covering cost of 1999 tax increase  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Tax rebate checks mailed to New Jerseyans in
September were supposed to offset school tax increases for homeowners. But
published reports say the savings aren't adding up for a lot of the Garden
State's 566 municipalities, with the 1999 tax rates exceeding the amounts of the
checks.
<P>
	   Statewide, the rebates averaged $120. The average tax increase last year was
$135, according to the Star-Ledger of Newark, which cited data from the Office
of Legislative Services and the state Treasury Department in Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a tax cut but it was certainly a modest one. It's really kind of
laughable," Summit resident Bob Wolfenbarger told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfenbarger said he received a $76 rebate, which wasn't enough to cover the
$200 increase in 1999 property taxes on his home. But Wolfenbarger fared
slightly better than other homeowners in Summit, which got an average tax
increase of $399. Summit residents received the same amount in the rebate
program.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the program, which Governor Christie Whitman signed last April, the
rebate is calculated using the local 1997 school tax rate on the first $45,000
of a home's value. In that way, the amount each homeowner receives in a town is
the same.
</P>
<P>
	   "As my mother used to say, it's better than a sharp stick in the eye,"
Roosevelt resident Gayle Donnelly told the Asbury Park Press for Sunday's
editions.
</P>
<P>
	   Donnelly and her husband, David, said they recently sold their house in
Roosevelt because of the high taxes. Gayle Donnelly said the tax rebate the
couple received was $248, but also said the couple's school tax bill last year
amounted to more than $700.
</P>
<P>
	   The Star-Ledger reported 239 of the state's municipalities are paying more
than the statewide average increase of $135, the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman put the program to work amid hoopla, but also had asserted the
program wasn't meant to reduce property tax rates. Whitman instead urged local
governments and school districts to embrace structural change and reduce costs
through shared services, mergers and regionalization.
</P>
<P>
	   But critics maintain the state can do more. And the idea of merging doesn't
appeal to many.
</P>
<P>
	   The Asbury Park Press reported only 15 of the state's 566 municipalities
have applied for the $10 million Regional Efficiency Development Incentive
program, which was included in a $35 million package of bills Whitman signed at
about the time the tax rebate program was offered. The package was intended to
encourage local governments to share services.
</P>
<P>
	   In Roosevelt, for example, Mayor Michael Hamilton said residents have mixed
feelings about merging with other municipalities.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm willing to pay for it, even if I have to starve to death. It's a choice
and that's the way I feel," Roosevelt resident Sol Libsohn, 86, told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   Libsohn said although he would consider a merger under certain
circumstances, he like the borough the way it is.
</P>
<P>
	   Meantime, Whitman's proposed 2001 budget calls for boosting the statewide
average of the rebates to $240. But that wouldn't have kept up with the increase
in property taxes from 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   "Unless there is some dramatic change ... you're not going to be reducing
property taxes. You're just going to be reducing the rate of increase," said
Henry Coleman, director of Rutgers University's Center for Government Services.
</P>
<P>
	   Coleman said the state's total property tax bill has been increasing by $400
million to $500 million annually. The Star-Ledger reported the average 1999 tax
bill increased by 3.28 percent over the year previous, or from $4,109 to $4,244.
</P>
<P>
	   The New Jersey Policy Perspective, a think tank, recently issued a report
calling on the state to absorb 50 percent of local educational costs, increase
the state income tax, levy taxes on stocks and bonds, and expand NJ SAVER to
ease the tax bill for all property taxes, not just the school tax.
</P>
<P>
	   "The public's not getting the message that they are getting what the
governor argues is property tax relief. I think the issue remains a very, very
ripe one for the election in 2001," said Sen. Bernard Kenny, (D-Hudson). "The
property taxpayer is in no better shape than this."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
