<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Senate Candidacy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton on Sunday formally launched her
campaign for the U.S. Senate in a state she has called home for only a month.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am honored today to announce my candidacy for the U.S. Senate from New
York,'' she said as the crowd of 2,000 people in a gymnasium at a state
university campus in Purchase chanted ``Hillary! Hillary!''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I may be new to the neighborhood, but I'm not new to your concerns,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Recalling a speech she made at her college commencement at Wellesley in
1969, she said: ``I often return to one thing I said back then, that politics is
the art of making possible what appears to be impossible. I still believe that
today. We can do what seems impossible if we have the vision the passion and the
will to do it together.''
</P>
<P>
	   Her remarks were preceded by tributes from U.S. Sens. Charles Schumer and
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, and U.S. Reps. Nita Lowey of Westchester and Charles
Rangel of Harlem. They joined her on stage as she delivered her speech. On her
other side were President Clinton, her mother Dorothy and daughter Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton went on to describe her commitment to better schools, better health
care and gun control.
</P>
<P>
	   But she also took pains to describe herself as a ``new Democrat''.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't believe that government is the source of all our problems or the
solutions to them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The race for the Senate seat being vacated by Moynihan is expected to pit
Clinton against Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican mayor of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   No other first lady has ever run for public office. In doing so, Clinton
steps out of the long and scandal-scarred shadow of her husband. President
Clinton is said to be one of her top advisers as she resumes the career she put
aside to help him capture the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani has not made a formal campaign announcement, but he came on ABC's
``This Week,'' one of five TV talk shows he appeared on Sunday. When asked if he
planned to run, he said, ``Looks that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
