<HEADLINE> Croatians Choose in Runoff Election  </HEADLINE>
   By SNJEZANA VUKIC Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- Croats choose a successor Monday to the only
president they have known, selecting from two candidates who promise to end the
autocratic style of the late independence leader Franjo Tudjman and integrate
this Balkan country into Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   The runoff between Stipe Mesic and Drazen Budisa -- the top finishers among
nine candidates in Jan. 24 balloting -- is almost symbolic: Their personalities
are different, but their political distinctions are subtle.
</P>
<P>
	   Western governments like both of them. And regardless of who wins, the new
center-left majority in parliament plans to reduce presidential powers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's no more Tudjman, and that's what matters,'' said Nadja Marinovic, a
46-year-old dancer.
</P>
<P>
	   It took Croats only a month to completely change the political landscape of
their country after the Dec. 10 death of Tudjman, who ruled with an iron hand
since Croatia seceded from Yugoslavia in 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   In parliamentary elections Jan. 3, Tudjman's conservative Croatian
Democratic Union was swept away after nine years of majority rule in favor of a
Western-oriented coalition of Social Democrats and Social Liberals.
</P>
<P>
	   The change has been welcomed in the West as an opportunity for Croatia to
emerge from the political and economic isolation brought about by Tudjman's
defiance of Western demands for greater democracy and respect of human rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Suddenly, doors to the NATO's Partnership for Peace, the World Trade
Organization and even the European Union have been unlocked. And Croatia is
peering in.
</P>
<P>
	   Some Western leaders who stayed away from Tudjman's Dec. 13 funeral are
expected to attend the inauguration of the new president.
</P>
<P>
	   The parliamentary elections and the first round of the presidential contest
have showed that ``any government can be replaced, that nothing is eternal
anymore in Croatia,'' said columnist Slobodan Snajder of the independent
newspaper Novi list.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Nothing can stop the final democratization of this country,'' Snajder
said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first round, Mesic, a laid-back, witty politician, finished 13
percent ahead of Budisa, a serious-minded co-leader of the ruling center-left
coalition. Surveys show Mesic still ahead going into the finale.
</P>
<P>
	   For many Croats, it almost doesn't matter who wins.
</P>
<P>
	   Mesic and Budisa both support constitutional changes to curtail presidential
powers that critics say Tudjman abused. Both pledge to work closely with the
parliamentary government to carry out economic reforms. Both say integration
into Western institutions is their major foreign policy goal. Both describe
neighboring countries as friends.
</P>
<P>
	   The public is focusing on personality.
</P>
<P>
	   Mesic, Tudjman's close aide until 1994, is informal, relaxed, charming, his
supporters say. ``A hero of anti-Tudjmanism,'' said Jelena Lovric, a political
analyst for Novi list. For many Croats, Budisa, a former student leader jailed
under communism, has been a symbol of morality and patriotism for nearly three
decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1633 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
