<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Air Jet Returns to Airport  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- An Alaska Airlines MD-83 jetliner returned to Reno's
airport shortly after takeoff when the pilot reported problems with the
horizontal stabilizer -- the third such incident involving that jet model within
a week.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seattle-bound jet's problems Saturday night were similar to those
discussed by pilots in the tense minutes before Alaska Airlines Flight 261
crashed into the Pacific on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The cause of that accident, in which 88 people died, has not been
determined.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, an American Airlines MD-83 had trouble with its horizontal
stabilizer after takeoff from Phoenix. It returned safely to the airport.
</P>
<P>
	   Alaska Airlines does not plan to ground its 35 MD-83 jetliners or to make
any unscheduled maintenance checks, said Jack Evans, a spokesman for the
Seattle-based airline.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We obviously understand there's some stress out there,'' he said in a
telephone interview Sunday. ``Despite the accident, we're launching about 400
flights a day and trying to conduct the normal side of our business.''
</P>
<P>
	   The horizontal stabilizer is a wing-like part on the tail manipulated by the
pilot to provide balance along the entire fuselage. An MD-83 stabilizer is about
40 feet wide, according to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
	   Alaska Airlines believes the Reno problem occurred because pilots are being
overly cautious and running the stabilizer through several complete up-and-down
cycles before takeoff, ``overheating the motors,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seattle-bound jet, Flight 631, left Reno/Tahoe International Airport at
about 7 p.m. Saturday. It headed back after seven or eight minutes when the
pilot reported that the motors that control the stabilizer were operating
improperly, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
	   The pilot told passengers he had a major mechanical problem, said passenger
Dennis Smythe of Anchorage, Alaska. Smythe, who has a commercial pilots'
license, said the plane was moving up and down.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The pilot seemed like he was trying to get in control of our porpoising,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   As the plane crossed Interstate 80 on its descent, Smythe said he felt the
right wing pitch and wondered if the pilot was in control of the plane.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was a lot of crying and a lot of praying because a lot of people
were probably thinking about that (earlier) crash,'' he said. Passengers cheered
as the pilot made a rough landing.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Aviation Administration officials did not immediately return calls
seeking comment on the flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1637 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Speeds Up Reforms  </HEADLINE>
   By JAMAL HALABY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- King Abdullah II had a little advice for ministers and
business leaders disagreeing over how to bring about educational reforms in his
country.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Roll up your sleeves and get down to work,'' the 38-year-old king roared
as he presided over a meeting on upgrading the school system. ``Unless we move
fast on this track within a year or two, we risk losing the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
	   Since Abdullah became the surprise choice to succeed his father, King
Hussein, a year ago, the energetic and often impatient new leader's
preoccupation has been speeding up reforms in his destitute country.
</P>
<P>
	   Hussein, who died last Feb. 7, was credited with transforming a land of
nomadic Bedouins into a largely cosmopolitan nation that exports doctors and
engineers to the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
	   Challenges at least as great face his son.
</P>
<P>
	   Jordan is saddled with foreign debt of $7 billion and unemployment that
officially stands at 14 percent but is said to be nearly twice that. About 20
percent of its 4.8 million people live in poverty. Corruption is rampant, and
bureaucracy hampers foreign and local investment. The 1994 peace treaty with
Israel has brought little dividends, and the West and oil-rich Persian Gulf Arab
states have been hesitant to help.
</P>
<P>
	   Abdullah's hands-on approach has earned him the nickname ``Jordan's chief
executive officer,'' and his calls for greater public freedoms, civil rights,
social justice and equality have raised blood pressures in a government and
parliament dominated by conservative politicians.
</P>
<P>
	   The new king also has staged raids on state institutions to inspect the
services citizens receive. He personally fired two doctors in charge of the
public al-Bashir Hospital three months ago when they ignored his instructions to
fix two elevators. Abdullah sometimes posed as an old man, a television reporter
or a taxi driver -- a ploy that allowed him to freely listen to complaints from
his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
	   ``After my first several visits, it was like Elvis,'' a chortling Abdullah
told foreign media correspondents recently. ``There were sightings all over the
country, but what it did too, it created fear in the civil service.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``They started treating everybody as a king because they didn't know whether
the next guy standing in line was the (real) king,'' he said. ``Now people are
on their toes.''
</P>
<P>
	   Such moves have sent Abdullah's popularity soaring among younger Jordanians,
who had revered Hussein for his liberal outlook but see in the new king a
determination to make changes that would improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
	   ``King Hussein was the father of all Jordanians, but King Abdullah is the
brother of the Jordanians,'' said 39-year-old Samer Abed al-Hadi, a civil
engineer.
</P>
<P>
	   Until his father's deathbed decision, Abdullah was a tank company commander
with little experience in affairs of state. He was considered a long shot to
assume the Hashemite Throne -- one of the Middle East's key political posts --
since his uncle, Prince Hassan, had been crown prince since 1965. But Hussein
deposed Hassan just days before he died.
</P>
<P>
	   Abdullah was labeled a political novice, but has shown himself capable of
setting his own agenda.
</P>
<P>
	   He has forged crucial strategic alliances to ensure the survival of a
country that had been ostracized by the Arabs. Hussein was seen as favoring Iraq
during the 1990-91 Persian Gulf crisis over Kuwait, and vilified for his warm
ties with Israel when prospects for a Middle East settlement faded under a past
hard-line Israeli administration.
</P>
<P>
	   Abdullah has kept both Iraq and Israel at arms length, earning praise from
Persian Gulf Arabs and powerful neighbors like Syria, which had long accused
Hussein of being Israel's ``puppet.''
</P>
<P>
	   He also was able to end a rift with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who
distrusted Hussein's policy in the West Bank territory that Jordan ruled for 17
years until it was seized by Israel in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
	   Abdullah has gone out of his way to lend support for Palestinian calls for
an independent state in the West Bank and has vowed to cede authority over
Muslim shrines in traditionally Arab east Jerusalem to the Palestinians -- a
right claimed by Hussein, a descendant of the 7th Century Prophet Mohammad of
Islam.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past year, the king also has dismissed his uncle's loyalists in the
army, government, intelligence services, and even palace aides.
</P>
<P>
	   Support for Abdullah came from a royal family fearful over the fate of the
Hashemite dynasty amid speculation that Hussein's successor might be Prince
Hamzeh, then a 19-year-old college student.
</P>
<P>
	   Abdullah, Hussein's son from his marriage to Briton Toni Gardiner, named
Hamzeh -- Hussein's son from a later marriage to American-born Queen Noor -- as
heir to the throne in his first royal decree.
</P>
<P>
	   Hussein has three other sons and six daughters from four marriages.
</P>
<P>
	   Abdullah and his wife, Rania, have two children -- Prince Hussein, 5, and
Princess Iman, 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1638 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At least 60 people displaced from four north Jersey fires  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) - At least 60 people were homeless after four
large fires broke out in three northern New Jersey cities Saturday night and
Sunday morning.
<P>
	   A string of blazes in Union City, Jersey City, and Paterson displaced at
least 17 families, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Union City, a fire began inside the top floor of a three-story building
on Bergenline Avenue around 7 p.m. Saturday, and spread quickly to three others,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ten families living in the second- and third-floor apartments were able to
escape with minor injuries, according to Union City Mayor Rudy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
	   The fire was brought under control around 11 p.m., Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
	   Residents were able to pick up what was left of their belongings on Sunday
morning, but it was unclear if they would be able to move back in.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're still assessing the damage, and we're not sure if all four are
completely destroyed," said Garcia on Sunday. "We will need to determine if any
one of them have to be razed."
</P>
<P>
	   He said that decision will be made later in the week.
</P>
<P>
	   The fire was caused by a faulty lighting fixture in a third-floor apartment,
according to city spokesman Brian Stack.
</P>
<P>
	   In Jersey City, a father, his three children and a firefighter suffered
smoke inhalation Saturday in a three-alarm blaze that heavily damaged three
rowhouses on Zabrieski Street, which left at least seven families homeless,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Justo Madero, 44, and his three children, aged 2, 7 and 14, were taken to
Jersey City Medical Center, according to Steve McGill, assistant director of the
Jersey City Fire Department. The family lived on the second floor of a two-story
rowhouse where the fire began.
</P>
<P>
	   "The father threw them out the window of the second floor and then he jumped
out," said McGill on Saturday. "There were residents on the ground floor that
caught them."
</P>
<P>
	   The father also jumped, and was taken to the same hospital, suffering from
neck and back pains, McGill said. Madero was treated and released, according to
a nursing supervisor at Jersey City Medical Center. No information was released
on Madero's three children.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the 55 firefighters who battled the blaze was treated and released at
St. Francis Hospital for smoke exhaustion, according to a nursing supervisor.
</P>
<P>
	   McGill said the Red Cross was at the scene helping displaced families,
including residents of a four-story home converted into apartments, and a
two-story building housing an apartment over a bar. Both two-story buildings
were heavily damaged and two apartments in the taller building also were left
uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
	   McGill said the fire began about 4:30 p.m. and was extinguished by 7 p.m.
Its cause was still under investigation on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Paterson, firefighters en route to a one-alarm fire on Spring Street
around 6 a.m Sunday, noticed heavy smoke coming from a three-story building on
Main Street, said Deputy Chief Norman Morley.
</P>
<P>
	   The fire at 624 Main Street had spread to two others buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   About 20 residents were able to escape their second- and third-floor
apartments, but a dog on the second died, Morley said.
</P>
<P>
	   The fire is believed to have begun inside a vacant store on the first floor
of 624 Main Street, Morley said. It was brought under control shortly after 8
a.m.
</P>
<P>
	   A crane was demolishing the building Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   Residents were staying with relatives or at a nearby hotel, Morley said.
</P>
<P>
	   The fire was declared suspicious and is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   A one-alarm fire at Spring Street began outside the building and had spread
to the basement, officials said. No one was injured, and it was unclear how many
residents were inside the building, but they were able to return.
</P>
<P>
	   The fire was under control around 7 a.m., and was also declared suspicious,
pending an investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
