<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Refugees Tell of Horrors  </HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW KRAMER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- After enduring months of bombing and shelling,
at least 22 civilians emerged from hiding in Chechnya's capital only to be
deliberately killed by advancing Russian troops, human rights workers and
refugees say.
</P>
<P>
	   According to their accounts, the killings occurred between Dec. 22 and Jan.
21 as soldiers were searching for rebel fighters and allegedly looting homes in
the Staropromyslovsky district of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
	   Lying in a hospital bed in the neighboring republic of Ingushetia -- where
up to 250,000 Chechens have taken refuge from the war -- 40-year-old Kheida
Makhayuri recounted how she and two other women had come upon troops stealing
mattresses from an apartment building. Three soldiers led them to a Russian
checkpoint, then to a bombed-out building.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They said 'the commander ordered us to bind your eyes','' Makhayuri
recalled, her voice rising barely above a whisper.
</P>
<P>
	   The blindfolded women were terrified and held hands, and the soldiers shot
them from behind with assault rifles, she said. Makhayuri's companions were
killed instantly, but she was wounded in the shoulder and pretended to be dead.
</P>
<P>
	   The soldiers ripped her earrings off -- leaving a tear in her right ear --
and she feared they would cut her finger off when they had trouble twisting off
a ring. The soldiers piled mattresses on the women and doused them with
gasoline, but the fire failed to spread across the fabric because it was damp.
</P>
<P>
	   Makhayuri said she dared to move only about half an hour later when she
heard a bird land nearby, and she knew the soldiers had gone.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They left thinking I was dead,'' she said. A wad of gauze bandages covered
a bullet wound in her shoulder, and her legs had burns from the gasoline.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russian military has repeatedly denied that its troops have
intentionally harmed civilians in their drive to take over the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
	   But the New York-based Human Rights Watch group has documented eight
incidents in the Staropromyslovsky district in which it says a total of 22
civilians were killed. There are also unconfirmed reports of more than a dozen
other murders associated with an alleged weeks-long rampage in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A disturbing number of civilians have been murdered by Russian troops in
Grozny,'' said Peter Bouckaert, a researcher with Human Rights Watch. He accused
Russian commanders of turning a blind eye to the killings.
</P>
<P>
	   Saipudin Saadulayev, 39, a former oil worker and Grozny native, witnessed
Russian soldiers shoot an elderly man at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
	   The old man, Said Tugoyev, had spent five months in Grozny cellars. He
survived repeated bombardments -- only to be killed as he walked across a yard
to tell two Russian soldiers that civilians were in the basement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They shot him with a machine-gun and then a soldier leaned over and shot
him in the head,'' Saadulayev said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
