<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans demand figures on candidate's travel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Republicans renewed a demand Sunday that Hillary Rodham
Clinton account for costs of her campaign travels, saying the first lady has
made "more than 50" politics-related trips costing taxpayers far more than the
$34,000 her aides say has been reimbursed to the White House.
<P>
	   "It would be a good time for Mrs. Clinton to play fair with the people of
New York," Patricia Harrison, co-chair of the Republican National Committee,
told reporters just before Clinton formally declared herself a candidate for
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   "We want her to try to begin her campaign by telling the truth."
</P>
<P>
	   As first lady, Clinton travels with the security and other trappings of the
White House and her campaign is supposed to reimburse the White House Travel
Office for some of the costs, but neither of those entities has released figures
on how much has been spent or paid back, Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
	   The $34,000 Clinton aides have reported reimbursing is based on the price of
first-class travel. It is not intended to pay the full cost of security for the
first lady, for whom the price of travel soars because of her position as the
president's wife.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Harrison said Clinton's travel expenses don't add up.
</P>
<P>
	   "The taxpayers should not have to foot the bill for her trips," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Harrison said her office had found that Clinton's campaign travels were
"comparable" with those of Vice President Al Gore, which cost him $323,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's probable opponent in the Senate race, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, has
made 14 campaign-type trips costing $150,000, "all flights fully paid for,"
Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
	   On a TV news program earlier in the day, Giuliani himself acknowledged that
the line between his campaign and mayoral staffs had blurred at times, saying:
"There's always going to be questions about overlap."
</P>
<P>
	   A list compiled by the GOP about Clinton's campaign showed 51 appearances by
the first lady between July 7 and Dec. 22, 1999, most of them in New York state.
It also included fund-raisers in Massachusetts, Philadelphia, Chicago, Las
Vegas, Los Angeles, Cincinnati, Rhode Island and Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
	   And Harrison said the list was incomplete.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't know how many trips she has taken or how much they cost ... or
whether payment for trips has been made," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton campaign aides did not immediately return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
	   However, in a statement handed out at Harrison's news conference by a
Clinton campaign volunteer, Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson described the
Republican demands for disclosure as "negative attacks," and "politics - pure
and simple."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
