<HEADLINE> Allies, Opponents react to Hillary Clinton's announcement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Here are quotes in reaction to Hillary Rodham Clinton's
formal announcement of her candidacy Sunday:
<P>
	   --"Hillary, Eleanor Roosevelt would love you," said U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
	   --"You might ask the following question: How is it that the Democratic Party
can't come up with a candidate for the Senate from the state of New York?" said
New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Clinton's likely Republican opponent, on
CBS' "Face the Nation."
</P>
<P>
	   --"She unleashes people's energies. When you're in the Senate, you need to
bring people together and lift them up and she's very good at that," said
President Clinton in the 18-minute video, "Hillary," shown at the campaign
kick-off.
</P>
<P>
	   --"It's a great day for women and it's a great day for everyone who cares
about New York," said Kerry Kennedy Cuomo, daughter of the late Robert F.
Kennedy; Kennedy once represented New York in the U.S. Senate and like Clinton,
was from out of state.
</P>
<P>
	   --"Mayor Giuliani's live television appearances Sunday were typical New York
-- spontaneous, honest and direct," said Kim Serafin, spokeswoman for Giuliani's
campaign. "Mrs. Clinton's was typical Hollywood -- scripted, choreographed and
directed by others."
</P>
<P>
	   -- "She's got the smarts, she's got the heart, she's a fighter, she doesn't
take no for an answer, and we will make a great team in the United States
Senate," said U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., speaking in tribute to the
first lady before she made her announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   --"Hillary, please don't run," said state Assemblyman Dov Hikind,
D-Brooklyn, an Orthodox Jew who criticized Clinton's meeting with Suha Arafat
and her lack of a position on clemency for Jonathan Pollard, an American
convicted of spying for Israel. "New York Democrats are more disenchanted now
than they were six months ago. Democrats can do better."
</P>
<P>
	   --"The more people get to see and hear Mr. Giuliani, the better she'll do,
particularly upstate," said Michael Schell, chairman of the state Democratic
Party's Executive Committee and a former Jefferson County party chairman.
"Upstaters are really more Midwesterners."
</P>
<P>
	   --"We want her to try to begin her campaign by telling the truth," said
Patricia Harrison, co-chair of the Republican National Committee, at a Sunday
press conference where she accused the first lady of making many more trips
related to her campaign than she has reimbursed taxpayers for.
</P>
</TEXT>
