<HEADLINE> Many Protest Spanish Woman's Slaying  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL EJIDO, Spain (AP) -- Angered by the slaying of a Spanish woman, scores of
protesters armed with bats and sticks threatened a group of North Africans
Sunday, but riot police separated the groups without any reports of injury.
</P>
<P>
	   Police helicopters flew overhead as officers patrolled the streets of this
city of 50,000 in southern Spain, where hundreds of African immigrants work.
</P>
<P>
	   The standoff came a day after the stabbing death of 26-year-old Encarnacion
Lopez Valverde and the arrest of a Moroccan suspect.
</P>
<P>
	   Government officials who attended her funeral Sunday were attacked by
mourners outside the church.
</P>
<P>
	   Spanish television showed footage of Fernando Hermoso, the Spanish
government's top representative in Almeria, being punched in the head and back.
He and other officials rushed back into the church for safety.
</P>
<P>
	   Tensions have been high in El Ejido for the past two weeks following the
death of two Spanish farmers, allegedly at the hands of a North African.
</P>
<P>
	   They boiled over on Saturday after Lopez was stabbed to death while shopping
at a flea market. The newspaper El Pais said she was a month away from getting
married.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said a young man tried to steal her purse but she resisted, and was
stabbed in the abdomen. She died almost instantly, as other shoppers looked on
in horror.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities arrested a 20-year-old Moroccan immigrant. The Interior
Ministry's top representative in the surrounding Andalusia region, Jose Torres
Hurtado, said the man had a history of mental problems.
</P>
<P>
	   In the hours immediately after the stabbing, protesters overturned cars and
burned shops owned by Moroccans, Hanafi Hamza, president of the Association of
Moroccan Immigrant Workers in Spain, told the news agency Efe.
</P>
</TEXT>
