<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Court Denies Spy's Request  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY JACK KATZENELL Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's Supreme Court on Sunday refused to intervene to
help convicted American spy Jonathan Pollard win his release from a U.S. prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Pollard, a former civilian analyst for the U.S. Navy, was convicted of
espionage in 1985 for giving Israel tens of thousands of top-secret documents.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel has acknowledged that Pollard was its agent and every Israeli prime
minister has asked the United States to release him.
</P>
<P>
	   In its ruling, the Supreme Court rejected Pollard's request to appoint a
judge to oversee the government's efforts to release him, saying it is not the
function of the judiciary to supervise the day-to-day running of the government.
</P>
<P>
	   The three-judge panel said it ``believes that the government will fulfill
its obligations to take care of the needs of the petitioner and do what is
necessary to secure his release from prison.''
</P>
<P>
	   Pollard's wife, Esther, who was present in court, said she was dismayed by
the court's ``cavalier attitude'' to her husband's plight.
</P>
<P>
	   Pollard contended in his petition to the high court that since taking
office, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has cut off contact with him and has
not worked to release him.
</P>
<P>
	   Esther Pollard has accused President Clinton of reneging on a deal to
release her husband in 1998 as part of an Israeli-Palestinian peace accord
brokered in Wye River, Md. Clinton has said he is reviewing a clemency request.
</P>
<P>
	   The court also turned down a request to grant Pollard $1.75 million in legal
expenses as well as a request that it order the government to release documents
related to the case.
</P>
<P>
	   Pollard is being held at a federal prison in Butner, N.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1737 </TRAILER>
