<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldier Killed in Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
   By BUTROS WANNA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) -- A roadside bombing in southern Lebanon on Sunday
killed one Israeli soldier and injured seven others, prompting Israel to vow
retaliation against the Muslim guerrillas who claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli army said 1st Sgt. Jedidia Gefen, 20, was killed during the
evacuation of the area following the bombing, when Hezbollah fighters fired on
the troops. The death was the fifth Israeli fatality in southern Lebanon in less
than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The bombing is certain to escalate a week of fighting -- the worst in six
months -- which has claimed the lives of three Israeli soldiers, the No. 2
officer in the Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army militia and a Hezbollah
guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
	   An Israeli soldier also was killed in a guerrilla rocket attack Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past, Israel has sometimes responded to such attacks by launching
commando operations targeting guerrilla leaders deep inside Lebanon. Amid fears
that Israeli threats of retaliation could mean more such operations, the
Lebanese government put its armed forces on ``the highest state of alert,'' a
security official said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   The official said the move was made ``in anticipation of any possible
Israeli aggression.'' The orders applied to all army and police personnel and
their weapon formations -- units numbering about 85,000 that largely stayed out
of the fighting between Hezbollah and Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   Hezbollah claimed responsibility for Sunday's attack near Blatt, three miles
from the Israeli border, saying the group targeted an Israeli foot patrol of
nine soldiers.
</P>
<P>
	   As an Israeli unit rushed to evacuate the patrol, fighters pounded the area
with rockets, inflicting more casualties, a Hezbollah statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   The attack was ``in retaliation to repeated Israeli aggression,'' the
statement issued in Beirut said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hezbollah is trying to oust 1,500 Israeli troops and 2,500 SLA militiamen
from a buffer zone Israel established in 1985 to protect its northern towns from
guerrilla attacks. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to withdraw
from South Lebanon by July, and he reiterated that Sunday despite the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli army said seven soldiers were wounded, four of them seriously.
The casualties were evacuated by military helicopters to hospitals in Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   Witnesses in government-controlled territory facing the Israeli-occupied
zone said Hezbollah supporters broadcast details of the attack over loudspeakers
from cars and mosques.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak promised retaliation, increasing the specter of more tit-for-tat
attacks along the last active Arab-Israeli warfront.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel ``will retaliate for any attack coming from south Lebanon and if it
is Hezbollah, then we will hit Hezbollah,'' Barak said in Jordan following talks
with King Abdullah II.
</P>
<P>
	   The largest partner in Barak's coalition, the ultra-Orthodox Jewish Shas
party, demanded Sunday that peace talks with Syria be suspended until Damascus
stops Hezbollah from attacking Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak needs Shas' support to push a peace treaty with Syria through
parliament and a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
	   In light of the escalation in Lebanon, Shas Health Minister Shlomo Benizri
told Israel TV, ``Why do we have to make an agreement with Syria?''
</P>
<P>
	   Israel maintains that Hezbollah could not operate without the consent of
Syria, which wields enormous power in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday Hezbollah's leader, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, threatened to fire
Katyusha rockets at Israel in retaliation for Israeli airstrikes on a southern
Lebanon village that wounded seven civilians and a commander of the guerrilla
group on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Nasrallah said the strike violated an April 1996 agreement designed to
protect civilians.
</P>
<P>
	   The stepped-up Hezbollah attacks and increased Israeli losses further
complicate efforts to get Syrian-Israeli peace talks going again. Barak had
demanded that Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, rein in Hezbollah before
the U.S.-brokered talks resume.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli army in Jerusalem kept news of Sunday's guerrilla attack under
wraps, as is usually the case until the deceased's next of kin are notified.
</P>
<P>
	   An Israeli army spokesman, however, confirmed there was an incident in
southern Lebanon in which several Israeli soldiers were wounded. The spokesman
did not provide further details.
</P>
<P>
	   A few hours after the guerrilla attack, Israel sent its jets to fire several
missiles in two retaliatory bombing raids on Jebal al-Botom, an area on the edge
of the occupied zone from which guerillas are thought to launch their attacks.
There was no word on casualties from the afternoon airstrikes, which the Israeli
army confirmed.
</P>
<P>
	   Hezbollah said in a statement Sunday that one its fighters, Ahmed al-Ashhab,
28, died Saturday from wounds suffered in recent fighting. It did not elaborate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
