<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramsey Father Denies Suspect List  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- In his only sworn testimony since his daughter was
killed in 1996, John Ramsey denied reports that he and his wife gave police a
list of suspects in the murder of 6-year-old JonBenet.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Unfortunately, a lot of people had keys to our house -- contractors,
plumbers, cleaning ladies, neighbors,'' Ramsey said in a deposition. ``We
honestly don't think we know anybody that could be this evil.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ramsey gave the deposition in October 1998 as part of a libel suit filed by
Boulder photographer Stephen Miles, who had sued Ramsey and the National
Enquirer after an October 1997 article referred to Miles as a drug addict and a
pedophile.
</P>
<P>
	   The article promised an ``Exclusive interview with the man Ramseys say
killed JonBenet.'' It quoted a ``source close to the Ramseys'' but didn't quote
Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit was dismissed and the judge unsealed Ramsey's 110-page
deposition in November. The Daily Camera reported its contents Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We never gave a list to the police of people we thought could be
responsible,'' said Ramsey, who has otherwise never given sworn testimony during
the investigation into his daughter's death.
</P>
<P>
	   Ramsey was asked if he suspected anyone of having killed his daughter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let me say two things. One, when you have something like this happen in
your life, you lose trust. Virtually anyone. So do you suspect everyone? Yes,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Secondly, I try to remind myself to not rush to judgment, as obviously
happened in this case, and I don't want to be guilty of that myself.
Unfortunately, you suspect everyone.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ramsey said his daughter's death took an emotional toll and that he was
taking an anti-depressant medication at the time of the deposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1803 </TRAILER>
