<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton announces Senate candidacy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) - Surrounded by family and almost 2,000 cheering
supporters, Hillary Rodham Clinton declared Sunday "I may be new to your
neighborhood, but I'm not new to your concerns," as she launched her campaign
for senator from the state she has only called home for a month.
<P>
	   "I am honored today to announce my candidacy for the U.S. Senate from New
York," she said as the crowd in a state university gymnasium chanted "Hillary!
Hillary!"
</P>
<P>
	   Recalling a speech she made at her college commencement at Wellesley in
1969, she said: "I often return to one thing I said back then: That politics is
the art of making possible what appears to be impossible. I still believe that
today. We can do what seems impossible if we have the vision the passion and the
will to do it together."
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton, her mother Dorothy and daughter Chelsea were on one side
of the stage as she spoke, along with U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. On the
other side were U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer, and U.S. Reps. Nita Lowey of
Westchester and Charles Rangel of Harlem, who had spoke in tribute to the first
lady.
</P>
<P>
	   Behind them all hung a red, white and blue "Hillary" banner - no last name,
just "Hillary" - bearing the address for her Website, www.Hillary2000.org.
</P>
<P>
	   In a switch of their usual roles, the president played the supportive spouse
while the first lady took center stage. Although the president helped write her
speech, he did not speak during the event.
</P>
<P>
	   Over and over again, Clinton pledged "I'll be on your side" as she described
her commitment to better schools, better health care, environmentalism and gun
control.
</P>
<P>
	   She went on to outline her support for a wide variety of other issues:
reviving the economy of upstate New York, working for passage of a comprehensive
nuclear test ban treaty and support of peace from Northern Ireland to Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   But she also took pains to describe herself as "a new Democrat" who supports
balanced budgets and welfare reform. "I don't believe that government is the
source of all our problems or the solutions to them," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The race for the Senate seat being vacated by Moynihan is expected to pit
Clinton against Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican mayor of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton has often criticized the mayor's combative style, and while she
didn't mention him by name Sunday, she pledged to would work against "the
divisive politics of revenge and retribution. ... I'll work to lift people up,
not push them down."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton also tried to get a little New York swagger into her delivery.
</P>
<P>
	   "I know it's not always going to be an easy campaign, but - hey! THIS is New
York," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   No other first lady has ever run for public office and in doing so, Clinton
steps out of the long and scandal-scarred shadow of her husband. Bill Clinton is
said to be one of her major advisers as she resumes the career she put aside to
help him capture the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   There is little real doubt that Clinton will face Giuliani, but the mayor
has not made his own formal campaign announcement. About the closest he's come
was on ABC's "This Week," one of five TV talk shows he appeared on Sunday. When
asked if he planned to run, he said, "Looks that way."
</P>
<P>
	   Recent polls have shown Giuliani with a slight lead over Clinton and running
even with her among women voters. That's a far cry from a year ago when talk was
fresh about a possible Clinton campaign that many doubted would ever come to
pass. Sympathy was strong from the Monica Lewinsky scandal and polls showed the
first lady well ahead of the mayor if she did run.
</P>
<P>
	   Five months later, she formed a Senate committee and began raising money for
the race. At Moynihan's sprawling farm on a bright July day she kicked off a
summer-long "listening tour" of the state that bled over into the fall and took
her from Broadway to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
	   By December, she was assuring supporters she intended to run. In early
January, she moved into a $1.7 million house in suburban Westchester County just
north of New York City to establish residency in the state she decided to adopt.
President Clinton said he plans to move there when he leaves the White House at
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Other than a closeness to her new home, political experts said there was
good reason for Clinton to stage her announcement in Purchase, which lies in
Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
	   "When duck hunting, one goes where the ducks are," Republican consultant Jay
Severin explained. "The independent suburban ducks are the ducks in this
campaign that are yet to be bagged."
</P>
<P>
	   In statewide races, suburban voters from Westchester County and Long Island
are considered a key to success and a Marist College poll released Friday showed
Giuliani leading in the suburbs, 56 percent to 34 percent, his strongest showing
in any region of the state.
</P>
<P>
	   While Giuliani dismissed the Clinton announcement as "a Hollywood type of
thing," a top Democratic strategist not connected to the Clinton campaign said
it served a real purpose, especially for a famous out-of-towner still viewed
skeptically by many New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
	   "It makes people understand this is for real and not a joke. It's not a game
anymore," Hank Sheinkopf said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton campaign arranged for about 500 house parties to be held
simultaneously around the state for more than 20,000 supporters who would watch
the announcement on television and then listen in on a conference telephone call
from the candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Clinton was to fly to Buffalo to begin a cross-state tour that
would take her to Rochester on Tuesday, Syracuse on Wednesday and Albany on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   As of the end of last year, she had raised $8 million and Giuliani, who
started fund raising three months earlier, had raised almost $12 million. It is
expected to be the most expensive Senate race in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
	   In seeking to replace Moynihan in the Senate, Clinton hopes to make another
kind of history. No woman has ever been independently elected to statewide
office in New York. Former vice presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro
unsuccessfully sought the Democratic Senate nomination in 1992 and 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
