<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Cleric Denies Terror Links  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Lawyers for a Muslim leader in Texas denied accusations by
federal prosecutors that he served as an intermediary for Osama bin Laden's
suspected terrorist network.
</P>
<P>
	   Moataz Al-Hallak, imam of the Islamic Society of Arlington mosque, provided
only religious advice to a pilot on how to handle the purchase of a small jet in
accord with Islamic law, said his lawyer, Stan Cohen.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane crashed in the early 1990s while being used by one of bin Laden's
businesses, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Al-Hallak was questioned about a jet purchase by a New York federal grand
jury investigating bin Laden's activities, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Al-Hallak has not been charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The whole thing is crap,'' Cohen said in Sunday's Dallas Morning News.
``If they had anything on Al-Hallak, they would have indicted him a long time
ago.''
</P>
<P>
	   In a late December court filing, prosecutors cited the plane deal to support
their charge that Al-Hallak ``provided cover'' for the business activities of
Wadih El Hage, a bin Laden associate. They contend that Al-Hallak ``facilitated
the purchase of a jet plane for bin Laden after bin Laden relocated to the
Sudan.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bin Laden, a Saudi millionaire exile, is accused of masterminding the 1998
bombing of two U.S. embassies in Africa. The attacks in Kenya and Tanzania
killed 224 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   El Hage, a friend of Al-Hallak and member of his mosque, is jailed in New
York on federal charges of aiding an alleged international conspiracy by bin
Laden to murder Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen said Al-Hallak shuns violence, does not know bin Laden and has not
been associated with any of his enterprises.
</P>
<P>
	   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in New York,
declined to comment on the airplane transaction.
</P>
<P>
	   El Hage has pleaded innocent but remains jailed without bond and is
restricted from contacting Al-Hallak.
</P>
<P>
	   Sam Schmidt, an attorney for El Hage, said his client's contacts with
Al-Hallak did not involve bin Laden's operations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In our papers, we indicated that the communications between El Hage and
Al-Hallak had nothing to do with terrorism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors have called Al-Hallak ``a contact point for El Hage's
co-conspirators'' and cited documents linking the two men. They also mentioned
that Al-Hallak had obtained ``business equipment'' for El Hage including a
combat knife and professional lock-picking sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1822 </TRAILER>
