<DOCNO> APW20000206.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Threats Overshadow Talks  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL SHIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- U.S. and South Korean officials plan sensitive
arms reduction talks this week amid North Korean threats that it would resume
testing its long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
	   The North Korean threats, made over the weekend, heightened concerns of a
possible arms race between the on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
	   The two-day U.S.-South Korea meeting in Hawaii starting on Tuesday continues
a series of missile nonproliferation talks between the allies which began in
1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest round in Seoul in November made little progress, with South Korea
resisting U.S. efforts to restrict its program to develop a longer-range missile
capable of hitting any part of North Korea.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We anticipate progress in this week's talks,'' said Chang Chul-kyun, a
spokesman for Seoul's Foreign Ministry. ``We need a missile strong enough to
provide a deterrent to North Korean threats.''
</P>
<P>
	   Chang said the talks in Hawaii will center on the issue of allowing the
United States to get involved in every stage of South Korean missile
development. Seoul has rejected the U.S. request.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the weekend, North Korea strongly protested South Korea's plan to build
a commercial ``satellite launch station'' by 2005, arguing that it is a disguise
for development of long-range ballistic missiles. The North accused Washington
of supporting the program.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The U.S. application of double standards strengthens our will for test and
development of missile,'' the North's foreign news outlet, KCNA, said in a
report.
</P>
<P>
	   North Korea, the report said, will ``immediately and unhesitatingly take a
strong countermeasure'' when the South's ``satellite launch station'' is
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
	   North Korea's missile capability is a matter of grave concern to the United
States. The reclusive country is believed to have missiles capable of reaching
Hawaii and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
	   Last September, North Korea agreed to forgo a test of a newly developed
longer-range missile for the duration of talks with the United States. In
return, Washington lifted some of its half-century-old economic sanctions on
North Korea.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the moratorium, North Korea rattled nerves in Asia and Washington by
testing a rocket that flew over Japan and landed in the Pacific Ocean in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1830 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Talks Suspended  </HEADLINE>
   By SAMAR ASSAD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian and Israeli peace negotiators suspended talks
Sunday to wait for U.S. proposals to get them back on track, a senior
Palestinian negotiator said.
</P>
<P>
	   The negotiations are aimed at meeting a Feb. 13 deadline for the outline of
a final peace agreement between the two sides. They were suspended on what was
to have been the seventh of 10 days of marathon talks, senior Palestinian
negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo told The Associated Press in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are waiting for the Americans, nothing can happen until they come back
with responses,'' Abed Rabbo said.
</P>
<P>
	   Larry Schwartz, a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Tel Aviv, confirmed the
U.S. efforts. But, he said, the sides should continue direct talks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is the most fruitful way to make progress,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli officials refused to confirm whether the negotiations -- often held
at a secret location -- were indeed canceled. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
visiting King Abdullah II in Jordan, said Israel continued to insist on direct
talks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think it is our responsibility with the Palestinians to get to a
solution,'' he said in comments translated from Hebrew by Israeli foreign
ministry officials. Abdullah sent his foreign minister to Cairo later to brief
visiting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on the meeting with Barak.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israelis object to U.S. intervention. Both sides believe President
Clinton is seeking a legacy in his last year in office and is likely to press
Israel into concessions.
</P>
<P>
	   The marathon peace talks are addressing thorny final status issues,
including the future of Jerusalem, refugees and borders between Israel and a
future Palestinian state. But the dispute that led to the suspension centers on
an interim issue -- a 6.1 percent withdrawal from the West Bank that Israel has
promised to carry out this week.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israelis want to hand over mostly uninhabited stretches of West Bank
land to Palestinian control. But the Palestinians want populous Arab suburbs of
Jerusalem, a city both sides claim as their capital.
</P>
<P>
	   The Palestinians say Israel's failure to take their considerations into
account on the less important interim issues makes negotiating the crucial final
status issues impossible.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There has been no accurate, honest implementation of what was signed
between us and Barak himself,'' Arafat told reporters in Gaza after returning
from consultations with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Palestinian and Israeli officials acknowledge now that the Feb. 13
deadline is likely to be missed.
</P>
<P>
	   After the breakdown, both sides began round-the-clock consultations. In
addition to meeting Mubarak, Arafat sent envoys to Jordan and Egypt. Barak flew
to Jordan on Sunday to consult with Abdullah about the breakdown with the
Palestinians, as well as the stalled Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
	   In Jordan, Barak threatened to retaliate against Muslim militants targeting
Israeli soldiers in South Lebanon, but stressed that he will stick to his
previous pledge to withdraw from the area by July.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Whoever hits us in South Lebanon, we will hit him back,'' Barak told
reporters after a two-hour meeting with Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
	   His comments came hours after an Israeli soldier was killed in a roadside
bomb in Israeli-occupied South Lebanon. The Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrilla
group claimed responsibility. The soldier was the fifth Israeli fatality in less
than two weeks in South Lebanon, the last active Israeli-Arab warfront.
</P>
<P>
	   Standing next to Barak on Sunday, Jordanian Prime Minister Abdur-Ra'uf S.
Rawabdeh said King Abdullah reiterated to Barak Jordan's support for Syria,
Lebanon and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
	   A communique issued after the talks said Abdullah urged Barak to ``remove
the obstacles facing the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations, because this track
constitutes the core of the peace process.'' The communique, read over Jordan
radio, said Abdullah also urged Barak to give the Syrian talks the care they
deserve because ``the Syrian leadership is committed to achieving a just
peace.''
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere Sunday, top Egyptian, Jordanian, Palestinian and Israeli officials
met in Cairo to discuss the fate of Palestinians displaced in the 1967 Middle
East war. They said a technical committee on displaced persons will meet
regularly beginning in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Both sides have agreed to discuss the issue multilaterally with Jordan and
Egypt. Jordan and Egypt have hosted hundreds of thousands of displaced
Palestinians since the war, and Israel and the Palestinians disagree about
whether those people should be allowed to return to their homes. Israel has said
it will allow only a few thousand to return since it has already let more than
66,000 people back in since 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
