<HEADLINE> Britain Millennium Dome Chief Fired  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The chief executive of Britain's troubled Millennium Dome has
been sacked and replaced with a French executive who helped reverse the fortunes
of Disneyland Paris, the company that runs the dome said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Pierre-Yves Gerbeau, 34, takes over from Jennie Page, 55, said Bob Ayling,
chairman of the New Millennium Experience Company. Gerbeau was operations
director at Disneyland Paris,
</P>
<P>
	   News reports said sponsors of the $1.2 billion dome had demanded action
after a series of setbacks, including problems with getting guests to the grand
opening on Dec. 31. When the dome opened to the public on Jan. 1, there were
long lines for some attractions.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, a day after Page was fired, the company announced that attendance
in January was just 366,000, well short of the figure needed if the dome is to
reach its target of 12 million visitors for the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Cabinet Office Minister Lord Falconer denied the government was behind the
sacking, although it has been embarrassed by problems at the dome. ``This is a
board decision,'' he said in an interview with British Broadcasting Corp. radio.
</P>
<P>
	   Dome officials said Gerbeau, who joined Disney in 1991, was a key player in
transforming Disneyland Paris from a commercial disaster into one of Europe's
most successful theme parks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
