<DOCNO> APW20000206.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group: NATO Killed Yugo Civilians  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Last year's NATO bombing campaign in the former
Yugoslavia killed about 500 civilians in 90 separate incidents, a human rights
group concluded after an independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   NATO, which is reviewing the Human Rights Watch report, said it took
``scrupulous care'' to avoid civilian casualties but was unable to make an
educated estimate of deaths and injuries during the 78-day bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All too often, NATO targeting subjected the civilian population to
unacceptable risks,'' Kenneth Roth, executive director of Human Rights Watch,
said in the investigation report released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York-based international monitoring organization conducted a
three-week inquiry in August. Investigators went to 91 cities and towns and
inspected 42 sites where civilians were killed.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation found no evidence of war crimes but concluded NATO
violated international humanitarian law by not properly warning civilians and
failing to identify them in road convoys and other bombing targets.
</P>
<P>
	   Alliance aircraft also attacked targets of questionable military value and
used imprecise bombs near populated areas, Human Rights Watch charged.
</P>
<P>
	   NATO says it has received the report and is studying it, NATO spokesman Lee
McClenny. He said it is impossible for NATO to give a solid estimate of the
number of civilian casualties in the campaign to end violence by Serb-led
Yugoslav security personnel against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
	   McClenny stressed NATO's deep regret for civilian casualties but said such
incidents must be weighed against the enormity of the NATO's mission to halt ``a
systematic policy of ethnic cleansing, deportation and persecution.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have to repeat that we took scrupulous care to avoid all possible
civilian casualties,'' McClenny said.
</P>
<P>
	   The bombing eventually drove Yugoslav soldiers and police from Serbia's
southern province. Serb officials have said as many as 5,000 civilians were
victims of NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
	   The pullout of Serb-led forces opened the way for an international
peacekeeping force in Kosovo, now administered by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   A Pentagon spokesman, Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, said last week that U.S.
officials never have come up with a figure on numbers of either civilians or
Yugoslav security forces killed in the Kosovo campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We felt that we couldn't do a particularly accurate job of that
estimation,'' Quigley said. But he added, ``This was an extremely carefully
planned air campaign and was the most accurate air campaign in history,
period.''
</P>
<P>
	   Quigley acknowledged ``unintentional civilian deaths'' but said, ``We tried
very, very hard to minimize those numbers, and we think we did a very good job.
But it wasn't perfect.''
</P>
<P>
	   Last June, the American Association of Jurists and other Western and Russian
law experts alleged in a report to a special Balkans war crimes court in the
Netherlands that the U.S.-dominated bombardment violated international law by
recklessly killing civilians. The U.N. court's prosecutor, Carla Del Ponte of
Switzerland, denied that a formal investigation of NATO was under way but said
her staff had looked into the allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   The Human Rights Watch report found about one-third of the 90 incidents
where civilians died occurred in Kosovo; many were killed during attacks on
military forces in the field or on the move.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigators found seven incidents related to attacks on convoys
particularly troubling and questioned whether NATO pilots flew too high for
accurate identification of their targets.
</P>
<P>
	   Some civilians may have been killed while being used as ``human shields'' by
the Yugoslav military, as in a village called Korisa where 87 people died on May
13, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 30 incidents happened in densely populated urban areas, including
six in the Yugoslav capital, Belgrade, despite the use there of so-called
``smart weapons.'' Cluster bombs, which release small bomblets to cause a wide
area of smaller explosions, killed between 90 and 150 civilians, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We used cluster bombs during the conflict,'' Pentagon spokesman P.J.
Crowley said Saturday. ``They were effective weapons in terms of denying Serbia
the use of aircraft or airfields to threaten our forces.''
</P>
<P>
	   A third of all incidents and more than half the deaths resulted from attacks
on questionable targets, the report said. Attacks that killed civilians but
served no military purpose included the bombing of Serbia's radio and television
headquarters in Belgrade, a Belgrade heating plant and seven bridges that were
not major transportation routes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 1901 </TRAILER>
