<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Party Candidate Wins in Japan  </HEADLINE>
   By GARY SCHAEFER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- A candidate backed by Japan's ruling coalition won an
important local election Sunday, giving a badly needed victory to Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi's government.
</P>
<P>
	   Fusae Ota's victory makes her Japan's first woman governor, succeeding Knock
Yokoyama, who stepped down in December amid charges that he sexually harassed a
campaign worker.
</P>
<P>
	   The Osaka prefectural election has been closely watched since opposition
lawmakers walked out of Parliament last month in protest over the forced passage
of a bill to reduce the 500-seat lower house of parliament by 20 seats.
</P>
<P>
	   A poor performance Sunday by candidates supported by the ruling coalition
would have been seen as a sign of public disapproval and probably would have
encouraged the opposition to prolong the boycott.
</P>
<P>
	   The coalition, however, had little to worry about. Ota received 1,380,583
votes in the final count. She was followed by Makoto Ajisaka, who was backed by
the Japan Communist Party and pulled in 1,020,483 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   Ota, a former senior bureaucrat with the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry, stressed in her campaign the need to support businesses as Osaka
struggles with the rest of Japan to recover from economic recession.
</P>
<P>
	   Ota, 48, said in a television interview Sunday night that she would feel
``great responsibility'' as the first woman governor in Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Osaka is a city of small and medium sized firms and I will make the utmost
effort to stimulate economy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Osaka prefecture is an important commercial area that includes Japan's
second-largest city, Osaka. It is 250 miles west of Tokyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
