<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Militant Calls for Nonviolence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- A leader in the insurgent group that assassinated
Egyptian President Anwar Sadat urged his organization Sunday to quit fighting
and pursue Islamic goals peacefully.
</P>
<P>
	   Osma Ayoub Sidiq said in a statement faxed to The Associated Press in Cairo
that the violence of Jihad is no longer in the interests of Muslims.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am calling on all my brothers inside and outside Egypt to halt military
operations and direct their efforts to Islam's biggest causes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   If the call is endorsed by other Jihad leaders, it would mean that
leadership of both of Egypt's two main militant groups would have called for a
change to nonviolent tactics. Leaders of Islamic Group called for a cease-fire
in 1997, but the move has not been endorsed by all members.
</P>
<P>
	   Jihad, which means holy war, killed Sadat in 1981. It is believed to be in
the throes of a leadership crisis. Recent reports in the Arabic press suggested
that its leader, Ayman al-Zawahri, had resigned over a strategy dispute.
</P>
<P>
	   Al-Zawahri is believed to be close to Osama bin Laden, the Afghanistan-based
Saudi dissident wanted for the bombing of the U.S. embassies in east Africa in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Some Jihad members were apparently opposed to al-Zawahri's decision to ally
the group with bin Laden in a coalition dedicated to attacking American citizens
and interests.
</P>
<P>
	   It is thought that Sidiq's call is in line with those Jihad leaders who
wanted to distance the group from bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
	   Sidiq, who has been sentenced in absentia to 40 years imprisonment for
insurgency, suggested that members should strive to ``liberate Jerusalem'' from
Israeli control. He did not explain whether this should be by peaceful or
violent means.
</P>
</TEXT>
