<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Defends Special Interest Cash  </HEADLINE>
   By EUN-KYUNG KIM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain, the Republican presidential candidate
who is barnstorming the country on a promise to break the grip of special
interests, on Sunday defended accepting contributions from such groups. Chief
rival George W. Bush honed his case against McCain with plans for a new TV ad
and a hard-hitting stump speech.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I welcome the support of anyone in the form of $1,000 contributions, but
they know clearly well where I stand, they know clearly I want to break the iron
triangle,'' McCain said on ABC's ``This Week'' as the GOP campaign entered an
intense two weeks of campaigning before South Carolina's high stakes Feb. 19
primary. A loss in South Carolina would critically damage either campaign,
though McCain has less room for error because Bush is better funded and
organized.
</P>
<P>
	   The Arizonan, whose push to overhaul federal campaign finance laws is the
centerpiece of his campaign, was accused Friday by Bush of engaging in
``Washington double talk'' for attacking special interests while courting their
support.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, who chairs the Senate Commerce Committee, recently came under fire
for writing letters on behalf of powerful interests and accepting contributions
from donors who often have business before his committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, stopped short of calling McCain a
hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Senator McCain sees himself and portrays himself as an advocate of
campaign finance reform, as somebody who is cleaner than anyone else around the
table, and yet he has accepted contributions and sought contributions from
people with legislation pending before his committee,'' Rove said on CBS' ``Face
the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush plans to sharpen his message against McCain beginning Monday with a
speech in Delaware that aides say will draw distinctions between the reforms
Bush has achieved as governor of Texas and the lack of progress made by
politicians in Washington, specifically McCain. Bush, who came out swinging at
McCain after losing to him in New Hampshire, plans to touch on a range of issues
to make the case against Washington-style politics and McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   The Texas governor also planned to unveil a new ad this week accusing McCain
of breaking his promise to run a campaign free of attacks. McCain, who made the
pledge in a Michigan debate last month, has since raised questions about Bush's
Social Security plan and, in a more subtle fashion, the Texan's qualifications
for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
	   Debate footage will be featured in the ad, which ``will remind voters that
John McCain made a promise not to run negative ads and then he has run them,''
said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky replied that Bush's campaign is behind
third-party ads critical of the senator, and he pointed out that a veteran's
activist blasted McCain in the presence of Bush at a recent South Carolina
event.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They're accusing us of going negative? That's the pot calling the kettle
black,'' Opinsky said. ``John McCain's ads are factual.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain himself said there was nothing hypocritical about accepting
contributions from lobbyists, including some who represent clients with
interests before the committee.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to get money from everybody in America and if someone who has a
special interest wants to give to my campaign and they're interested in reform,
that's fine,'' he said. ``The message is clear -- there's going to be a change
in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, who plans a major fund-raiser Thursday in Washington that will be
broadcast via satellite to about 30 sites nationwide, said many of his
contributors support his efforts to change the way political campaigns are
financed.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has been on a roll since defeating Bush in the New Hampshire primary
last Tuesday. He said he expected attacks from members of the GOP establishment
who feel threatened by his efforts, and they are now ``coming at me from all
sides.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm like Luke Skywalker trying to get through the Death Star,'' McCain
quipped.
</P>
<P>
	   In a news conference late Sunday, McCain labeled ``bizarre'' a story in the
Arizona Republic on Sunday that tried to link the senator to a murder
investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was briefly interviewed by a sheriff's deputy because the murdered
man, Ronald J. Bianchi, had once spread rumors about McCain. McCain's campaign
provided The Associated Press affidavits from four involved parties, including
two county investigators, who said they believed McCain had nothing to do with
Bianchi's death.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's so bizarre, it speaks for itself,'' McCain said of the story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
