<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reagan Too Ill For Celebration  </HEADLINE>
   By DARA AKIKO WILLIAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Ronald Reagan was too ill to join the 700 people
who gathered Sunday at the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library and Museum to
celebrate his 89th birthday.
</P>
<P>
	   Nancy Reagan said Friday on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' show that her husband
-- diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease in 1994 -- was ``doing as well as can be
expected'' considering the disease is progressive.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When I listened to him, it was like I was listening to my father. And
that's probably the biggest compliment I can give someone,'' Jan Tornquist of
Santa Barbara said Sunday during the library's barbecue and vintage car show.
``He was so down to earth.''
</P>
<P>
	   None of Reagan's relatives attended the celebration, but Nancy Reagan's
bright red 1970 Ford Custom Ranch Wagon was on display.
</P>
<P>
	   The library described the cars in the context of Reagan's life: a Ford
Roadster Deluxe with a rumble seat from 1932, the year he graduated from
college; a Chevrolet pickup truck from 1937, the year he worked on his first
movie ``Love is on the Air''; and a silver Rolls Royce Wraith Coupe from 1952,
the year he and Nancy married.
</P>
<P>
	   The car show was held to promote a new commemorative California license
plate that features a photo of Reagan wearing a cowboy hat. The Department of
Motor Vehicles must receive 5,000 applications by the end of the year for the
Reagan plate before it will be issued. About 2,000 orders have been placed, said
library spokeswoman Teri Saucier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 2009 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
