<HEADLINE> Sunday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ------
Bouchard: Health Crisis Needs Cure
</P>
<P>
	   LAVAL, Quebec (AP) -- The Quebec government still has to cure its ailing
health care system before it can call another sovereignty referendum, Premier
Lucien Bouchard insisted on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   But he denied he was stalling calling a vote that opinion polls have
consistently shown is not wanted by Quebecers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't subordinate any referendum to the complete settlement of the
health problem,'' he told a news conference after a speech to about 400 members
of the Parti Quebecois governing council.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But I think the people need and they expect us to bring forward the kind
of solutions which will comfort them that we are in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
	   The premier ended the two-day meeting by urging delegates to push for
sovereignty but also left no doubt there was no imminent referendum on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Seal Hunters May Face Confrontations
</P>
<P>
	   ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) -- Seal hunters could face increased
confrontations with protesters during this spring's cull unless more ice gathers
soon in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, warns a top mammal biologist.
</P>
<P>
	   Usually, the seal hunt occurs many kilometers off shore in thick, tightly
packed fields of ice.
</P>
<P>
	   Pierre-Yves Daoust, a seal expert with the Atlantic Veterinary College in
Prince Edward Island, says that a lack of ice in the Gulf could drive thousands
of female harp seals inland to whelp.
</P>
<P>
	   And that would allow activists easier access to disrupt the hunt, Daoust
says.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is very little ice right now in the Gulf,'' says Daoust, who acted
as an observer during the seal hunt off Newfoundland last year. ``We could have
even more confrontation than when the seals are out on the ice floes in the Gulf
because it would be much more visible.''
</P>
<P>
	   The seal hunt generally takes place in mid-March on the ice floes off the
North Shore of Prince Edward Island
</P>
<P>
	   ------
British Columbians Flout No-Smoke Law
</P>
<P>
	   VANCOUVER (AP) -- Where there's no smoke, there's fire.
</P>
<P>
	   One month into British Columbia's sweeping ban on smoking in restaurants,
bars and pubs, many customers are still lighting up.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the threat of mounting fines, some business owners say their patrons
can keep puffing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's not the right way to go about it,'' said Teri Burleigh, the manager
of the BX pub in Prince George, British Columbia
</P>
<P>
	   If tobacco smoke is so bad, the government should ban it, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'd be behind them 100 per cent,'' Burleigh said. ``But that's not how
they're going about it. Making us fight it at this level just isn't the way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
	   It's been a month since the toughest nonsmoking policy in the country --
possibly in North America -- kicked in throughout British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
	   As of Jan. 1, restaurants, pubs and bars became subject to the provincial
Workers' Compensation Board regulations aimed at protecting workers from the
effects of secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Report: Theft Search Spared Lockers
</P>
<P>
	   HALIFAX (AP) -- Navy detectives who searched HMCS Montreal for $32,500
stolen from the ship's safe did not check the crew's personal lockers, a newly
released report shows.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All areas on board with the exception of personal lockers were searched,''
says an investigation report obtained under the Access to Information Act.
</P>
<P>
	   The money, which disappeared last May and has never been found, could have
been stashed in someone's locker.
</P>
<P>
	   But investigators were unable to check the crew members' bed areas and
lockers because they're considered private space and require search warrants.
</P>
<P>
	   And no search warrants could be obtained because there wasn't enough
evidence to go before a judge, a military spokesman says.
</P>
<P>
	   The money -- 650 bills in $50 denominations -- disappeared from the pay
office safe sometime between May 27-31 while the frigate was docked in New York
during a visit.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Sparks May Fly When Parliament Resumes
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- There's bound to be fireworks Monday when Parliament resumes
in the midst of a government grants mess and debate on Quebec referendum
legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The feeding frenzy has already started,'' said Reform House leader Chuck
Strahl.
</P>
<P>
	   Several events have made federal Liberals an easy target for opponents in
the Commons, Strahl said, including a decision to help NHL teams that was later
dropped, a proposal to provide banks with tax relief and mismanagement of up to
$1 billion in Human Resources grants.
</P>
<P>
	   Finance Minister Paul Martin will deliver his seventh budget Feb. 28. With
surpluses expected to reach $100 billion over the next five years, Martin is
under increasing pressure to fund tax cuts and program spending.
</P>
</TEXT>
