<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wins Wrestling World Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Lincoln McIlravy, Cary Kolat, Joe Williams and Kerry
McCoy won gold medals Sunday to lead Team USA to the championship at the World
Cup of Freestyle Wrestling 2000.
</P>
<P>
	McIlravy's takedown with three seconds remaining against Yosmany Sanchez led
the U.S. team to a 19-10 victory over Cuba in Sunday's afternoon session.
</P>
<P>
	``I knew that I was really, really short on time,'' McIlravy said. ``This is
more of a complaint than a brag, but I've ended up winning a lot of those
matches through college and in international competition because I make some
mistakes early and have to come from behind. I'm really trying to eliminate
that.''
</P>
<P>
	The victory was McIlravy's fourth consecutive triumph over Sanchez, 24, who
finished seventh in the 1999 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
	``That really was amazing,'' U.S. coach Greg Strobel said of McIlravy, a
25-year-old from Iowa City, Iowa. ``A lot of people would just say: `Hey, that's
it. I can't win this.' But he just kept right on going. And that just sets the
tone for everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
	Kolat and McIravy carried that energy into the evening session by posting
technical falls during the United States' 22-9 victory over Russia.
</P>
<P>
	Kolat took a 10-0 decision over Russia's Zelimkhan Akhmadov in 2 minutes, 5
seconds at 138.75 pounds. McIlravy followed with an 11-1 victory over Zaour
Kazbekov in 5:51.
</P>
<P>
	Eric Akin opened the nightcap with a 10-6 victory over Russia's Maxim Molonov
at 119 pounds. After Russia's Miron Dzadzaev took a 7-3 decision over silver
medalist Eric Guerrero at 127.75 pounds, the U.S. quartet of Kolat, McIlravy,
Williams and Les Guthches reeled off four consecutive victories, the latter two
in overtime.
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Kouramagomed Kouramagomedov defeated U.S. Army Spc. Dominic Black 4-1
at 213.75 pounds. Super-heavyweight McCoy closed the match with a 4-0 decision
over Oleg Khorpiahov.
</P>
<P>
	Guerrero, Kolat and Williams also posted victories for the U.S. against Cuba.
McCoy won by forfeit over Cuba's injured Alexis Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
	In other matches, Iran beat Russia 17-15 in the afternoon session, and then
topped Ukraine 22-9 in the nightcap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 2103 </TRAILER>
