<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mavericks Set To Accept Rodman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Despite the inevitable distractions that
Dennis Rodman will bring to Dallas, the Mavericks are anxious to welcome the
Worm to their team.
</P>
<P>
	   Rodman, who signed with Dallas on Thursday, is in the process of moving from
Los Angeles to Dallas and is expected to make his Dallas debut on Wednesday when
the Mavericks play host to the Seattle SuperSonics. His first appearance with
the team will come at the Mavericks' next practice, either Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We discussed it and everyone was accepting and happy to have him on board,
so hopefully, he'll join us real soon because he still hasn't shown up yet,"
guard Steve Nash said Sunday before Dallas played Vancouver. "I'm excited, I
think it's going to be great. I think he's going to add a lot of positives to
our team."
</P>
<P>
	   Nash said he's not worried that Rodman's celebrated unorthodox lifestyle --
including some run-ins with the law -- will upset the team's mix, considering
the Mavericks have won nine of their last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's just a matter of us allowing him to affect us positively, and anything
that he would do to deter from our success just to ignore it and not allow it to
affect us," Nash said.
</P>
<P>
	   The players went so far as to hold a team vote last week in which they
expressed their approval of Rodman's signing.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was important to me because I share most everything with the team. I
don't know if it went the other way what we would've done," coach Don Nelson
said. "But they're like anybody else, they want to win and they think he can
help us win. Let's try it."
</P>
<P>
	   Nelson considers Rodman a good fit for the club, saying, "He brings what we
don't do, which is rebounds and defense."
</P>
<P>
	   Rodman, 38, played 23 games with the Los Angeles Lakers last season before
the team released him in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
