<DOCNO> APW20000206.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Sunday, Feb. 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hijacked Plane Lands in London
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- British police a hijacked Afghan passenger airliner landed at
London's Stansted airport early Monday. The plane was isolated on the airport
grounds so that officials could open negotiations with the hijackers. The Ariana
Airlines plane was seized earlier Sunday while on a domestic flight from the
Afghan capital, Kabul, to the northern city of Mazar-e-Sharif. The plane made
stops in Uzbekistan, Kazakstan and Russia before arriving in London just after 2
a.m. (9 p.m. EST Sunday). Officials say none of the people aboard the Boeing 727
had been harmed, although it remained unclear how many people were aboard.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton Announces Senate Run
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Becoming the first president's wife to run for
office, Hillary Rodham Clinton launched her Senate campaign today from the state
she has called home for only a month. The race for the seat being vacated by
fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan is likely to pit Clinton against
Republican New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in what could be one of the most
combative political campaigns in memory. Behind her, President Clinton; her
mother, Dorothy; and daughter Chelsea sat beaming as nearly 2,000 supporters
cheered.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russian Tanker Carried Iraqi Oil
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tests confirm a Russian tanker seized by the U.S. Navy in
the Persian Gulf was carrying Iraqi oil in violation of the U.N. economic
embargo, Defense Secretary William Cohen said today. The Volga-Neft-147 was
being taken to Muscat, the capital of Oman, and the Omani government will
determine the fate of the merchant vessel and its crew, Cohen told reporters
while flying back from Germany, where he attended a conference on European
security.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Last Grozny Rebel Holdout Falls
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GEKHI, Russia (AP) -- Federal troops have seized the last rebel stronghold
in Grozny, acting President Vladimir Putin said Sunday, pronouncing an end to
Russia's months-long drive to take the Chechen capital. Putin said federal
troops had taken control of the western Zavodskoi district of the capital and
raised the Russian flag over an administration building there. "A short while
ago, the terrorists' last bastion of resistance was seized," Putin said in an
interview with state-controlled ORT television. "So, we can say the operation to
liberate Grozny is over."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Library Celebrates Reagan's Birthday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- About 700 people gathered on a sun-drenched
Sunday afternoon to celebrate Ronald Reagan's 89th birthday with a vintage car
show, barbecue lunch and country music. The celebration was held at the Ronald
Reagan Presidential Library and Museum, which charged $15 for the lunch and
offered free birthday cake to all museum visitors. Reagan, who last visited the
library in May, was too ill to join the celebration. None of Reagan's relatives
attended the event, but Nancy Reagan's bright red 1970 Ford Custom Ranch Wagon
was on display.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pfizer To Acquire Warner-Lambert
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. has emerged the victor of a three-month
takeover battle for control of Warner-Lambert Co. Pfizer is expected to announce
tomorrow it is acquiring Warner-Lambert Co. for $84.4 billion in stock, in a
deal that will create the world's second-largest pharmaceutical company. The
combined company's medicine cabinet includes the impotence treatment Viagra and
Lipitor, the blockbuster cholesterol fighting drug. The deal will mark the end
of a takeover battle that started in November when Warner-Lambert announced a
$58.3 billion merger with its New Jersey neighbor American Home Products Corp.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World Beats North America 9-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Pavel Bure scored three goals, two set up by little brother
Valeri, and goaltender Olaf Kolzig played a rare shutout period as the World
team turned the 50th All-Star game into an uncommon rout, dominating North
America 9-4 at the NHL All-Star game today. The Bure brothers nearly connected
for another goal in a four-goal World third period, but Valeri disobeyed big
brother's instructions by passing up an open shot to try to feed Pavel again.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NFC Beats AFC 51-31
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HONOLULU (AP) -- Randy Moss set records with nine catches for 212 yards, and
Mike Alstott scored three touchdowns in the NFC's 51-31 victory over the AFC on
Sunday in the highest-scoring Pro Bowl ever. Arizona's Aeneas Williams and Tampa
Bay's Derrick Brooks returned interceptions for touchdowns as the NFC dominated
the game from the start in snapping a three-game AFC win streak. The 82 points
broke the record of 64 set in 1980. Moss, the 6-foot-4 Minnesota star selected
the MVP, used his height advantage to outleap the AFC defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 2201 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000206.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Brings Bodies to Police Station  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- An unidentified man turned up at a police station in central
Japan on Monday with the bodies of four people he said he had killed.
</P>
<P>
	   The man produced the bodies of two children and two women in a van at the
Gifu-Minami police station in Gifu city, 170 miles west of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese television reported that the victims were the man's two children,
his wife and her mother.
</P>
<P>
	   He admitted killing the four people but apparently gave no explanation as to
why, when, how or where he killed them, the police officer said on condition he
not be named.
</P>
<P>
	   According to National Police Agency records, 1,265 murders occurred in Japan
in 1999. That murder rate per capita is far lower than in many other developed
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 2209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
