<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Advance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar edged higher against the yen Monday morning in
light trading because of the Chinese New Year holiday in Hong Kong and
Singapore. Japanese stocks rose moderately.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 107.51 yen at late morning, up 0.07 yen from late Friday
in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 107.35 yen on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 111.86 points, or 0.57
percent, to 19,874.99 at the end of the morning session. On Friday, the average
closed down 23.29 points, or 0.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar drifted higher amid rising
Tokyo stock prices and some yen-buying interest from Japanese exporting
companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders expected the greenback to move in a narrow range for the rest of
Monday amid the market holidays in Hong Kong Kong and Singapore, Asia's other
big markets.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 105.67 yen, down from 106.67 yen
late Friday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices opened higher on buying of major high-technology
and communications-related stocks in line with Friday's gains in their U.S.
counterparts on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   "Although profit-taking interest is strong at current high levels, buying
has been spreading to those shares seen as laggards," said Sachio Ishikawa,
general manager at Chuo Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York on Friday, the Nasdaq Composite Index rose 33.17 points to
4,244.15, slipping above its previous record of 4,235.40, set Jan. 21. The Dow
Jones industrial average fell 49.64 points, or 0.4 percent to 10,963.80 at
Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was up 13.04 points, or 0.75 percent, to 1,754.26. The TOPIX closed up
11.74 points, or 0.68 percent, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8250
percent from Friday's finish of 1.8150 percent. Its price fell 0.09 point to
98.93. (km-dj)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 2230 </TRAILER>
