<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-06 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hijackings in Recent Years  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Some of the more dramatic hijackings in recent years:
</P>
<P>
	   -- Five hijackers seize Indian Airlines flight carrying 178 passengers and
11 crew members on Dec. 24, 1999, after its departure from Katmandu, Nepal. The
captors kill one passenger and release others in the early stages of the
hijacking. The hijackers leave the parked plane in Afghanistan with 155 hostages
on board on Dec. 31 after India agrees to release three prisoners.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Shiite gunmen hijack a Kuwait Airways jumbo jet en route from Thailand to
Kuwait on April 5, 1988, and divert it to Iran, Cyprus and Algeria. They demand
Kuwait free 17 pro-Iranian terrorists. The hijackers kill two passengers. They
free the rest on April 20 and are allowed to leave Algiers .
</P>
<P>
	   -- Shiite gunmen seize the TWA Boeing 727, forcing it to Beirut, Lebanon on
June 14, 1985. They demand the release of 700 Arabs held by Israel. A U.S. Navy
diver is killed and 39 Americans are held until they are released on July 1
after Syrian mediation.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Shiite gunmen seize a Kuwait Airways plane from Dubai, United Arab
Emirates on Dec. 3, 1984, and force it to Tehran, Iran. The hijackers demand
that the Kuwaiti government free 17 people convicted of carrying out bombings of
U.S. and French facilities in Kuwait. Two Americans are killed. The standoff
ends on Dec. 8 when Iranian security forces disguised as cleaners storm the
jetliner.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Three Pakistanis commandeer a Pakistan International Airlines plane on a
flight from Karachi to Peshawar on March 2, 1981 and force the craft to fly to
Afghanistan and then to Syria. Hijackers leave the aircraft on March 14 after
Pakistan agrees to free 54 political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Palestinian and German terrorists hijack an Air France airliner to
Entebbe, Uganda, on June 27, 1976, and demand the release of 53 pro-Palestinian
prisoners in Israel, Kenya and Europe. Israeli commandos raid the craft and
rescue the hostages on July 4. Four civilians are killed during the rescue
operation.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Members of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine divert an El
Al flight from Rome to Tel Aviv, to Algiers on July 23 1968. The last hostages
are released Sept. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-06-00 2247 </TRAILER>
