<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Spills Into Pa. Wildlife Refuge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Thousands of gallons of crude oil spilled into a
national wildlife refuge in southwest Philadelphia during the weekend after a
refinery pipeline began leaking.
</P>
<P>
	   The 24-inch pipe began leaking Saturday and spread about 25,000 gallons of
oil beneath the icy surface of a pond, officials said. Scientists aren't sure
how severely wildlife in the 1,200-acre reserve will be affected.
</P>
<P>
	   Clean up crews were working round-the-clock Sunday to remove the oil.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a very unique situation. We've never had, in my experience, an oil
recovery situation beneath the surface of ice,'' said John McCann of the Sunoco
Refinery, which operates the pipeline that bisects the John Heinz National
Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators won't know what caused the underground pipe to leak until they
dig it up, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
